Analysing ESG report using Natural Language Processing¶

Summary¶

Environment, Social and Corporate Governance (ESG) refers to the three central factors in measuring the sustainability and societal impact of an investment in a company or business. These criteria help to better determin the future financial performance of companies (return and risk).

This analysis extracts text from a ESG report in PDF format from the internet, performs NLP on these information, summaries the key ESG initiatives with WordClouds, TDIDFs and discovers topics by building a Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) model.

Given that ESG is a broad topic. Different companies focus on different aspects of ESG depending on their business operations and culture. One can potentially ingest more ESG reports from different companies across all sectors and industries to capture relevant ESG topics. This to be attempted in another analysis.

Enter required information about the report. Report must be in PDF format and downloadable from a URL.

  1. Company Name
  2. Company Ticker Symbol
  3. Year of the Report
  4. URL of the Report

Text Extraction¶

Extract information from the PDF report. This process may take some time. Do be patient.

You may skip to the last step of this section if you have previously extracted the contents and stored in a json file.

In [130]:
def extract_pdf(file, verbose=False):
    
    if verbose:
        print('Processing {}'.format(file))

    try:
        resource_manager = PDFResourceManager()
        fake_file_handle = io.StringIO()
        codec = 'utf-8'
        laparams = LAParams()

        converter = TextConverter(resource_manager, fake_file_handle, codec=codec, laparams=laparams)
        page_interpreter = PDFPageInterpreter(resource_manager, converter)
        
        password = ""
        maxpages = 0
        caching = True
        pagenos = set()

        content = []

        for page in PDFPage.get_pages(file,
                                      pagenos, 
                                      maxpages=maxpages,
                                      password=password,
                                      caching=True,
                                      check_extractable=False):

            page_interpreter.process_page(page)

            content.append(fake_file_handle.getvalue())

            fake_file_handle.truncate(0)
            fake_file_handle.seek(0)        

        text = '##PAGE_BREAK##'.join(content)

        # close open handles
        converter.close()
        fake_file_handle.close()
        
        return text

    except Exception as e:
        print(e)

        # close open handles
        converter.close()
        fake_file_handle.close()

        return ""
In [131]:
def extract_content(url):
    """
    A simple user define function that, given a url, download PDF text content
    Parse PDF and return plain text version
    """
    headers={"User-Agent":"Mozilla/5.0"}

    try:
        # retrieve PDF binary stream
        r = requests.get(url, allow_redirects=True, headers=headers)
        
        # access pdf content
        text = extract_pdf(io.BytesIO(r.content))

        # return concatenated content
        return text

    except:
        return ""

This \nESG report includes a discussion of Americans approach to \nmanaging our most material ESG issues, along with highlights of \nour progress and performance in 2021. Unless noted otherwise, \nperformance data is for the 12 months ending Dec. 31, 2021. \n\nAdhering to best practices for ESG disclosure, this report also \naligns with the recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-\nrelated Financial Disclosures (TCFD) and the standard for the \nairline industry developed by the Sustainability Accounting \nStandards Board (SASB). We view both of these reporting \nframeworks as important indicators of the ESG issues that \ninvestors and others consider most material. Regarding forward-\nlooking statements, please see the last page of this report.\n\nAbout American Airlines Group\nAmericans purpose is to care for people on lifes journey. Shares \nof American Airlines Group Inc. trade on Nasdaq under the ticker \nsymbol AAL, and the companys stock is included in the S&P  \n500. Learn more about whats happening at American by visiting \nnews.aa.com and connect with American on Twitter @AmericanAir \nand at Facebook.com/AmericanAirlines.\n\n1\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##MESSAGE FROM OUR CEO\n\nCEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nAs the world begins to emerge from the pandemic and \nreconnect, American Airlines is committed to living our \npurpose to care for people on lifes journey. People want \nto explore and make connections again, while businesses \nrecognize the importance of reestablishing relationships, \nand they are turning to American to make that possible. To \ndo so, we are focused on running a reliable operation and \nreturning American to profitability. And, thanks to the hard \nwork and dedication of our team, we are making strong \nprogress on both. \n\nOur environmental, social and governance (ESG) efforts \nare a key part of Americans success today and critical to \nbuilding a resilient airline that will thrive forever. At the \ncore, we are a people business, relying on our 127,000 \nteam members to fly millions of customers each year to \nthe important moments in their lives. Operating every \nflight safely and protecting the health and well-being of \nour team members and customers is the starting point for \neverything we do at American. \n\nWere also focused on ensuring we have the talent our \ncompany needs to grow and compete. Doing so requires \nrecruiting and advancing the best talent and creating a \nculture in which every one of our team members is valued, \nempowered and has the opportunity to grow at American. \nTo make that a reality, we are prioritizing diversity, equity \nand inclusion (DEI) throughout our organization. \n\nIm proud to say that in 2021 we met or exceeded the \ngoals we set to address our largest gaps in leadership \nrepresentation. We will continue to track representation \nclosely, because we know what gets measured gets done. \nIn 2022, we included DEI goals in the annual short-term \n\nincentive plan for our entire leadership team, encouraging all \nmanagers and above to be accountable for our performance. \n\nEqually essential to our long-term success is preparing our \nairline to thrive in a carbon-constrained future. To address \nclimate change, American continues to strive to achieve \nnet zero emissions by 2050 by running a more fuel-efficient \noperation, with more fuel-efficient aircraft, powered by \nlow-carbon fuel. In April 2022, we became the first airline \nin the world to receive validation from the Science Based \nTargets initiative that our intermediate emissions-reduction \ntarget complies with its rigorous criteria. In 2021, we used \nover 1.4 million gallons of sustainable aviation fuel (SAF), \nmaking us the only airline in the United States to report \nusing more than 1 million gallons of SAF. We also finalized \nagreements that bring our total SAF purchase commitment \nto date to over 120 million gallons. \n\nAs a result of these and other efforts, in 2021 American was \nincluded in the Dow Jones Sustainability North America \nIndex for the first time  the only passenger airline to be \nincluded. American is also proud to continue our support \nfor the United Nations Global Compacts Ten Principles, and \nour ESG efforts are integral to meeting that commitment. \n\nI am honored to add to the strong ESG foundation we have laid \nat American Airlines and to have the opportunity to support \nour incredible team as we build an even brighter future. \n\nRobert Isom | Chief Executive Officer\nJune 2022\n\n2\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##ESG STRATEGY\n\nCEO Message \\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nThe last two years have brought enormous change and disruption to our industry, economy and the \nworld. More than ever, rigorous management of environmental, social and governance (ESG) risks \nand opportunities is critical to the success of American Airlines and to the health of our planet. \nWe have long recognized the importance of these issues and have developed an integrated and \ntransparent approach to ESG management, measurement and reporting. That said, theres always \nroom for improvement, and we continue to look to best practices within and outside our industry  \nas we refine and strengthen our policies, practices and disclosures. \n\nOur Priority ESG Issues\n\nOur ESG strategy is focused on the topics that are most \nimportant to our company and our stakeholders. We \nperiodically conduct formal ESG materiality assessment \nprocesses, most recently in 2018, that serve as the founda-\ntion of our analysis of areas of risk and opportunity. And, \nthrough ongoing engagement across our company and with \na broad range of external stakeholders, we validate and, \nas needed, refine our assessment based on the input we \nreceive and changes in our operating environment. \n\nWe also continually monitor ESG trends, standards and \npractices relevant to our industry, and look to external \nreporting frameworks, including SASB and TCFD, as key \nindicators of investor perspectives on the most significant \nESG risks and opportunities for our company. In 2021, these \nactivities affirmed our focus on the following priority issues:\n  Climate change and fuel efficiency\n  Customer satisfaction and operational performance \n  Diversity, equity and inclusion (DEI)\n\n  Safety (including flight safety and team member health \n\nand safety)\n\n  Team member and labor relations\n\nDriving progress across all these issues is a key objective \nfor American. At the same time, we recognize that the \nbusiness landscape is evolving rapidly and that we must \nbe ready to address new areas of concern if and when they \nemerge. We will continue to seek stakeholder input while \nalso closely monitoring emerging ESG practices and trends. \n\nIn 2021, American joined the United Nations \nGlobal Compact, the worlds largest corporate \nsustainability effort. The index on page 53 guides \nstakeholders on where to find information on \nour efforts to implement the Global Compacts \nTen Principles.\n\n4\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\\\\ ESG StrategyESG STRATEGY\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nManagement and Governance \n\nSince ESG issues touch nearly every aspect of our \nbusiness, day-to-day management of individual elements \nis distributed throughout our operations and functions. \nAmericans Managing Director for ESG is responsible for \nguiding and coordinating our activities at the executive \nlevel. She receives guidance and feedback from a \ncross-functional and cross-operational group of senior \nleaders with responsibility for regularly assessing the \neffectiveness of our ESG strategy, its implementation \nand further integration of sustainability into our company \nstrategy and operations.\n\nAt the Board level, the Corporate Governance, Public \nResponsibility and Safety (CGPRS) Committee has primary \nresponsibility for overseeing ESG efforts. The CGPRS \nCommittee is regularly updated on the companys efforts \nrelated to sustainability and to addressing climate change. \n(See A Directors View on ESG on page 6.) \n\nClimate-related governance\nBecause climate change is a pressing challenge for our \ncompany and our planet, American takes a coordinated \napproach to ensuring we have robust governance of \nclimate-related risks and opportunities. It begins with \nBoard-level oversight and accountability and extends to \nour day-to-day operations. \n\nAmericans Board oversees our climate strategy as part of \nan enterprise-wide approach to risk management. Either as \na full Board or through one or more of its committees, the \n\nBoard reviews managements strategy and its assessment \nof material risks affecting our business. This includes \npotential climate-related risks. \n\nIn 2022, we formally assigned Chief Executive Officer \nRobert Isom, who also serves on our Board of Directors, \nwith responsibility for oversight of Americans climate \nchange strategy. In addition, climate-related issues are a \nstanding agenda item in the CGPRS Committees quarterly \nmeetings. The full Board receives updates as well at least \nthree times per year.\n\nAt the management level, responsibility for climate-related \nissues is embedded in senior roles across our company. \nFor example, the Airport Operations team does resiliency \nplanning for more frequent and severe weather events; our \nFuel Procurement team works to secure cost-competitive \nsupplies of sustainable aviation fuel (SAF); and our Flight \nOperations and Fleet Engineering teams are focused on \nimproving fuel efficiency in the air and on the ground. Our \nClimate Change Steering Committee  which is led by an \nExecutive Vice President and includes representatives from \nAirport Operations, Flight Operations, Technical Operations, \nCargo, Finance, Safety, People and Communications, Legal, \nGovernment Affairs and Investor Relations  provides \nguidance across these efforts. And Americans Managing \nDirector of ESG is responsible for developing and \ncoordinating the companys overall climate strategy and \ndriving its implementation.\n\nPublic Policy and Political Contributions\nPolitical, legislative and regulatory decisions can play \nan important role in Americans success, and we have \nadopted policies that guide our participation in these \nprocesses. Reflecting best practices, our Statement on \nPublic Policy Engagement and Political Participation \nprecludes American from using corporate funds for \ncontributions to candidates, political party committees \nand political action committees. Our Board reviews  \nthis statement annually and last approved a revision  \nin January 2022.\n\nWe do not use corporate funds for the election-\neering activities that the Supreme Court allowed in \nCitizens United. On the rare occasion when we do \nuse corporate funds to contribute to a state or local \nballot initiative or a 501(c)(4) organization, we have \ncommitted to disclose that contribution. In 2021, \nAmerican did not make any political contributions.\n\nThe CGPRS Committee oversees the companys \nmajor advocacy priorities and activities, political \ncontributions and principal trade association \nmemberships. For example, we have committed to \naligning our lobbying efforts with the priorities and \ngoals of the Paris Agreement, the international treaty \non climate change. In 2022, we will also assess our \ntrade groups alignment with this agreement and \ninclude that in our reporting. \n\n5\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\\\\ ESG StrategyESG STRATEGY\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nHow do you view ESG in the context of the other priorities \nover which the Board has oversight? \nESG is an important part of Americans long-term strategy. \nWe dont look at ESG and other strategic priorities as \neither/or decisions. The health of people and planet are not \nseparate from the financial health of our company.\n\nCan you provide an example?\nLet me give you two examples. More than 90% of \nAmericans total carbon footprint comes from jet fuel, so \nour fleet renewal program and our work to run our flight \noperations more efficiently are an absolute win-win. Its \nthe same with DEI. The company that wins is the company \nthat has the best talent, and DEI is about having access to \nthe best talent available. If you create an environment that \ncombines empathy and action, where people with different \nperspectives and experiences can come together and move \nquickly and in concert, you get better decision-making \nacross the board. \n\nHow is your committee working to drive progress on  \nESG at American? \nYou have to examine performance, and you have to do that \nin a consistent way. The committee is deeply engaged on \nour climate strategy and receives regular updates about \nprogress toward our goals and data on our performance. Its \nthe same with safety, which is the backbone of American, \nas well as DEI. This year, we added DEI metrics to the \ncompanys management compensation plan, which is \nimportant because it clearly signals where the organization \nstands and propels progress. \n\nImportantly, the committee is trying to provide oversight \nin a way that is not boilerplate. We are looking for \nmanagement to talk to us about challenges and how theyre \nworking to find solutions. Even if we miss our goals, we can \ndig into why and what its going to take to correct course. \nA strong safety culture  which we have at American  \ndepends on zero blame, only learning. The same goes for \nother aspects of ESG. \n\nWhat does corporate leadership on ESG require?\nThere are categories of decision-making where the \ninformation and data arent perfect, but even with \nuncertainty, you can and must make decisions. That \ndoesnt mean you operate just on instinct or without \nthe facts, but you try innovative approaches with the \nbest information you have. Some will fail, some will be \nsuccessful  but progress depends on thoughtful action.\n\nBut one courageous company  or even several \ncompanies  is not enough to move the market or the \nworld. We need to build a cohort of leaders who are willing \nto work together and act boldly. Take climate, for example: \nWe need the environmental and scientific communities, \nbut we also need the business sector and government \nto step up. For our part at American, we recognize the \nurgency of climate change and that for our business  and \nfor our customers, shareholders and team members  it is \nin our interest to help find solutions, working with others \nboth within and outside our industry. Leadership requires \nthinking on a collective level, not solely an enterprise level.\n\n6\n\nIN CONVERSATION: \nA Directors View on ESG\n\nSue Kronick is the former Vice Chairman of Macys, Inc., \nand has served on the American Airlines Board of Directors \nsince 2015. In early 2022, she shared her perspectives on \nESG as an independent director and Chair of the CGPRS \nCommittee.\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\\\\ ESG StrategyESG Change\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nAt American, we know that the challenge of climate change is acute and imminent, and we recognize \nour industrys contribution to it. We believe we have an obligation to our customers, team members, \nshareholders and the communities we serve to transition to operating a low-carbon airline. To make \nthat happen, we have set aggressive climate goals that match the seriousness of the challenge, and \nweve laid out a clear plan for how we will achieve them. \n\nOur aim is to achieve net zero greenhouse gas (GHG) \nemissions by 2050, and we have set an intermediate \ntarget to drive progress toward that goal. In April 2022, \nwe received validation from the Science Based Targets \ninitiative (SBTi) that our intermediate 2035 GHG reduction \ntarget complies with the SBTi criteria. That makes us the \nfirst airline globally to achieve this milestone. \n\nAmericans science-based target is to reduce carbon \nintensity, which means GHG emissions per unit of \npassenger and cargo payload that the airline transports, \nby 45% by 2035, compared to a 2019 baseline. In setting \nthis goal, we are committing to reduce the intensity \n\nIn 2022, American became the first airline \nglobally to receive validation from the \nScience Based Targets initiative (SBTi) that \nour 2035 GHG reduction target complies  \nwith the SBTi criteria. \n\nassociated with the entire life cycle emissions of jet fuel. \nThis includes both direct emissions (Scope 1)  which \nare primarily from the jet fuel used in flight  and the \nemissions from the production of the jet fuel the airline \nuses (Scope 3).\n\nAmerican has also committed to reduce by 40% the \nemissions from the production of the electricity we \npurchase (Scope 2) by 2035, also with a 2019 baseline. \nScope 2 emissions are a small part of our overall GHG \nemissions, but an important focus for reducing the \nimpacts of global warming.\n\nWe are also engaging with and supporting efforts to \ndrive broader action on climate across the public and \nprivate sectors. For example, American is a signatory to \nthe Business Ambition for 1.5C campaign, and we joined \nthe United Nations-backed Race to Zero. We are also an \nanchor partner, together with other leading companies, of \nBreakthrough Energy Catalyst (see page 13). We know \nthat our ability to achieve our climate goals depends on \nother actors  within the aviation industry and beyond \nit  and we intend to be a leader in helping drive the \noperational, policy and technological changes needed to \nadvance the transition to a low-carbon economy. \n\nOUR CLIMATE GOALS\n\nACHIEVED\n\nReceived SBTi validation  \nFOR OUR 2035 GHG EMISSIONS REDUCTION GOAL\n\nIN PROGRESS\n\nACHIEVE ABSOLUTE REDUCTION OF \n50m gallons of jet  \nefficiency initiatives \n\nfuel from fuel- \n\nBY 2025\n\nSOURCE \n\n2.5m GJs of  \n\ncost-competitive  \nrenewable energy\n\nBY 2025\n\nREPLACE \n\n10% of our jet  \nfuel with SAF \n\nBY 2030\n\nREDUCE \n\nGHG emissions  \nintensity by 45% \n\nBY 2035\n\nScope 2 emissions  \n\nREDUCE \n\nby 40% \nBY 2035\n\nAchieve net zero  \n\nemissions\n\nBY 2050\n\n9\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nquickly and be successful if lower-probability or higher-\nconsequence risks manifest. As a result, another core part \nof our strategy is making ongoing investments in deepening \nour understanding and analysis of climate-related risks \nand opportunities to inform our evolving approach. For a \ndetailed discussion of our climate-risk assessment process \nand findings, see page 22.\n\nAs part of our ongoing analysis of transition climate risks \nand opportunities, we incorporate a price on carbon when \nestimating Americans potential obligations under the \nCarbon Offsetting and Reduction Scheme for International \nAviation (CORSIA), European Union Emissions Trading \nSystem and other possible regulatory programs that may \nimpact our operations. The carbon prices used for these \nestimates are based on cost projections from respected \n\nOur strategy for reaching net zero emissions \nby 2050 is focused on running an ever more \nfuel-efficient operation, with more fuel-efficient \naircraft, powered by low-carbon fuel.\n\nexternal sources. We have also begun incorporating a \nshadow price on carbon in evaluating investments in our \nfleet and fuel efficiency initiatives, as well as sustainable \naviation fuel (SAF) purchases.\n\nOur Climate Strategy\nMore than 90% of Americans total carbon footprint, \nincluding our Scope 3 emissions, comes from our use of jet \nfuel, so our strategy for reaching net zero emissions by 2050 \nis focused on running an ever more fuel-efficient operation, \nwith more fuel-efficient aircraft, powered by low-carbon fuel. \n\nTo do so, we are working to drive progress across several \nkey levers  some of which we have the ability to influence \ndirectly, and some of which will require action and collabora-\ntion within our industry, across sectors and by policymakers. \n(See chart on the following page.) \n\nIntegrating climate risk into our strategy and investments\nUnderpinning our strategy is the in-depth analysis we \nconducted in 2020  and updated and expanded in 2022   \nto understand the climate-related risks and opportunities \nfacing our company. We studied their potential impacts on \nour business, operations and the broader environment in \nwhich we work under different warming scenarios. \n\nWhile there is considerable uncertainty about the \nlikelihood and operational and financial consequences of \nthese scenarios, the direction and potential magnitude of \nclimate-related risk is clear. Our strategy is designed to \nposition American to anticipate, mitigate and respond to \nclimate-related risks and to thrive in an uncertain future. \nIt includes making targeted investments to address the \ndemonstrated and high-probability risks associated with \nclimate change that may affect our business, such as the \nimpact of extreme heat on aircraft or of sea level rise at our \nmajor hubs. It also includes strategic investments, based on \nthe best available information, to enable American to adapt \n\n10\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate with our supply chain and other Scope 3 emissions.\n\nESTIMATED INDUSTRY UPSTREAM  \nWELL-TO-PUMP JET FUEL EMISSIONS*\n\n   50% Extraction\n  6% Crude Transport\n   38% Refinery\n  6% Product Transport\n\nAbout 76% of Americans Scope 3 \nemissions are from jet fuel, including \nthe fuel used by our contracted regional \ncarriers and the upstream emissions \nfrom our fuel suppliers. These upstream \nwell-to-pump emissions  including \nextraction, crude transport, refining and \nproduct transport  constitute approxi-\nmately 20% of petroleum jet fuel life cycle \nemissions.* To move the needle on our \nScope 3 emissions, we know we must work \nwith our fuel suppliers to better under-\nstand the steps they are taking to reduce \nemissions within their operations.\n\nIn 2021, we initiated a process to engage with our key fuel suppliers, with the initial  \nobjectives of improving data quality and our reporting on their upstream emissions, as  \nwell as understanding their resiliency to the physical risks from climate change. \n\nAlso in 2021, we improved our CDP Supplier Engagement score to an A. Given the nature of the climate challenge \nand of our industry, transitioning to low- and no-carbon \naviation depends on innovations in airframe, engine and \nfuel technologies, combined with effective policies that \ndrive those innovations and the necessary investments \nto bring them to scale. American is committed to \ncollaborating across the public and private sectors \nto help advance the policy and technology solutions \nneeded to get to net zero.\n\n/\n)\n \n(\n/\n.\n \n1\n)\n\n\n\n\nOne way we are doing that is as an anchor partner of \nBreakthrough Energy Catalyst (Catalyst), a ground-\nbreaking program within the larger Breakthrough Energy \nnetwork that is working to accelerate the development \nand commercialization of critical technologies for \ndecarbonization. Catalysts initial focus is on SAF, green \nhydrogen, long-duration energy storage and direct air \ncapture. It is bringing together partners from across the \npublic and private sectors, using a creative, blended \nfinancing approach that combines philanthropic, below-\nmarket and low-cost capital to make targeted investments \nto scale and reduce the green premium of new decar-\nbonization technologies. American has committed to \ninvest $100 million in the effort. Catalyst also brings \ntogether experts to develop policy recommendations for \n\naccelerating innovation and encouraging the widespread \nadoption of clean technologies. \n\nClimate technologies moving out of the lab and into the \nmarket often struggle to access capital due to higher risk, \nlower demand and lesser returns than exist for more mature \nsolutions. Catalyst helps finance first-of-their-kind projects \n\nthat deploy these innovative climate technologies, with the \naim of reducing risks, driving down costs and creating a \nsmoother pathway to widespread market adoption.\n\nPoint of vulnerability\nEarly Deployment \n\nFunding Gap\n\nPoint of vulnerability\nCompany Building\n\nPoint of vulnerability\nTech Development\n\n\x03\x1c.$\x1e\x01\n\x13 . \x1c-\x1e#\n\n\x06\x1c-\'4\n\x14/\x1c-/0+\n\n\x15 \x1e#)*\'*"4\x01\x05 1 \'*+( )/\x01\x1c)\x1f\n\n\x04*(+\x1c)4\x01\x030$\'\x1f$)"\n\n\r\x1c-" \x14\x1e\x1c\' \x01\n\n\x04*(( -\x1e$\x1c\'$5\x1c/$*)\n\n\x15 \x1e#)*\'*"4\x01\x0e\x1c/0-$/4\n\n13\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Fleet Renewal\nA key way to reduce our jet fuel usage  and therefore our \ncarbon footprint  is to replace older, less fuel-efficient \naircraft with new, more efficient ones. Since 2013, American \nhas invested more than $24 billion in modernizing our fleet \nby taking delivery of more than 600 new aircraft. Over the \nsame period, we retired 670 older, less fuel-efficient planes \nthrough the end of 2021. The result: American has the \nyoungest mainline fleet among U.S. network carriers, with \nan average age of 11.3 years old. At the end of 2021, 55% of \nAmericans mainline fleet was 10 years old or less.\n\nNew aircraft, such as the Boeing 787 Dreamliner, Boeing \n737 MAX and the Airbus A321neo, which incorporate the \nlatest engine and airframe technologies, made up 17% of \nour total available seat miles (ASMs) in 2021. Approximately \n$3.6 billion, or 12% of our revenue during the year, stemmed \nfrom passengers flying on the market-leading, fuel-efficient \naircraft in our fleet. The Boeing 737 MAX 8 reduces fuel use \nand CO2 emissions by an additional 14% over todays other \nmost fuel-efficient single-aisle airplanes  and 20% better \nthan the original 737 next generation aircraft when they first \nentered service.1 The Airbus A320neo family delivers 20%  \nfuel savings and CO2 reduction compared to previous \ngeneration Airbus aircraft.2\n\nLargely as a result of flying these more efficient aircraft, \nAmerican has improved fuel efficiency by 10.2% compared \nwith 2013, based on fuel burn per ASM. That adds up to  \n1.9 billion gallons of fuel saved and 19 million metric tons  \nof CO2 avoided.\n\n1 \n\n https://www.boeing-me.com/en/products-and-services/commercial-air-\nplanes/737-MAX.page.\n\n2  https://aircraft.airbus.com/en/aircraft/a320/a320neo.\n\nCEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nAt the end of 2021, American had 42 Boeing 737 MAX 8 \naircraft in our fleet. In January 2022, we announced our \nplans to exercise purchase options on an additional 30 \nBoeing 737 MAX 8 aircraft, bringing our firm order total \nto 88 additional deliveries through 2026. We also had 44 \nAirbus A321neo aircraft in our fleet at the end of 2021 and \nhave agreed to purchase an additional 76 for delivery \nthrough 2026. Of the firm order for 76 aircraft, 50 are the \nlatest generation and long-range Airbus A321XLR aircraft. \nBy 2026, we expect approximately 34% of our ASMs will be \nflown by the Boeing 787 Dreamliner, Boeing 737 MAX and \nAirbus A321neo. \n\nIn recent years, we have also made significant investments \nin updating our regional aircraft fleet. Smaller aircraft \nand shorter flights  which devote a larger percentage \nof overall flight time to takeoff and landing  come at \na fuel-efficiency cost. However, our regional carriers \nenable American to serve many smaller communities \nand low-density markets that dont have the passenger \ntraffic to support larger jets. This service plays a vital role \nin connecting members of those communities to other \npeople, places and economic opportunities. American is \ncommitted to providing industry-leading regional service, \n\nAmerican received a CDP Climate Change \nscore of A in 2021  the highest score \namong airlines in North America, and one of \nonly two airlines globally to score that high. \n\nwhile continuously working to make that service more \nfuel efficient. This includes retiring a number of small \nregional jets in recent years and replacing them with \nlarge regional jets  such as the Embraer 175 and the \nBombardier CRJ900  which are on average more fuel \nefficient. We also continue to evaluate emerging low-carbon \ntechnologies such as electric- and hydrogen-powered \naircraft, which hold promise for use in regional air travel. \n(See accompanying box.) \n\nAdvancing Next-Generation Aircraft\nDecarbonizing aviation requires near-term action \nto improve efficiency and significantly expand the \nuse of SAF, but it will also depend on technological \nadvancements that enable aircraft to be powered \nby low- and no-carbon fuel sources such as green \nhydrogen and electricity. American continues \nto engage with our aircraft suppliers and other \nkey players in the aviation sector to support the \nadvancement of next-generation aircraft.\n\nOne initiative that will further this goal is Americans \ninvestment in Vertical Aerospace Ltd., which is devel-\noping an emissions-free electric vertical takeoff and \nlanding (eVTOL) aircraft. Designed for transporting \ncustomers quickly both between and within cities, \nVerticals piloted four-passenger VX4 is projected to \nbe capable of traveling distances over 100 miles at \nspeeds over 200mph, while producing minimal noise \nand zero operating emissions.\n\n14\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nFlight Operations and Efficiency\nAt the same time as we are adding new, more fuel-efficient \naircraft to our fleet, we continually look for ways to operate \nour existing fleet as efficiently as possible. Doing so enables \nus to both save on jet fuel costs and reduce GHG emissions. \nAmerican has set a target to achieve a 50 million-gallon \nabsolute reduction in jet fuel use by 2025, using 2019 aircraft \nas a baseline. That is, aircraft in our fleet as of January 2019 \nthat continue to fly through 2025 will use 50 million gallons \nless fuel as a result of fuel-efficiency initiatives.\n\nWe have implemented a host of fuel-savings initiatives, both \non the ground and in the air, focused on three key areas:\n  Operating more efficiently on the ground. We have \n\nimplemented a number of operational changes to reduce \non-the-ground fuel use. For example, in 2021, American \ndeveloped a new application to optimize how we assign \ngates to aircraft at Dallas-Fort Worth International \nAirport (DFW). This new approach to gating optimizes \nfor taxi time, maximizes on-time arrivals, reduces ramp \ncongestion, minimizes gate conflicts, saves fuel and \nreduces GHG emissions. Leveraging real-time Federal \nAviation Administration (FAA) flight data and routing \ninformation, we are using the new tool for all our DFW \nflights today; we also expect to expand its use to other \nairports. Based on the reduced taxi time resulting from \nuse of the tool today, we project full-year fuel savings of \n870,000 gallons at DFW alone, equal to more than 2,600 \nmetric tons of CO2.\nAmerican has also reduced the use of onboard auxiliary \npower units during flight preparation by connecting to \nless carbon-intensive electric ground power at the airport \nterminal. We have also increased our use of single-engine \n\nOUR FUEL-SAVINGS INITIATIVES ARE FOCUSED ON THREE KEY AREAS \nEstimated annual fuel savings and GHG emissions avoided\n\nOn the Ground\n60k metric tons  \nof CO2e avoided annually\n\nFlight Weight\n140k metric tons  \nof CO2e avoided annually\n\nIn Flight\n203k metric tons  \nof CO2e avoided annually\n\nSingle-engine taxi \n170k gallons saved\n\nAPU usage \n2m gallons saved\n\nEngine washing \n3.4m gallons saved\n\n\x84\x85\x83\x83\n\x84\x86\x83\x83\n\x84\x87\x83\x83\n\x84\x88\x83\x83\n\nScheduling \n870k gallons saved\n\nIn cabin \n4.1m gallons saved\n\nPaint \n1m gallons saved\n\nLighter seats \n6.9m gallons saved\n\nNew brakes \n2.8m gallons saved\n\nEn route updates \n4.1m gallons saved\n\nArrival fuel \n17.3m gallons saved\n\n15\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\ntaxi operation (i.e., using just one aircraft engine to taxi \nto the gate after landing), which reduces the carbon \nemissions produced by taxiing by 20%40%. In addition, \n\nwe have implemented new procedures for staggering \nflight departures and arrivals, which results in less time \nfor aircraft on the ramp and, therefore, less fuel use. \n\nIncreasing Efficiency by Modernizing Our Air Traffic Control System\nImproving the countrys network of aviation infrastructure, technology and services will increase operational \nefficiency and reduce jet fuel use. In turn, that will avoid millions of metric tons of CO2 emissions annually and help \nreduce aviations carbon footprint. Improvements in our Air Traffic Control (ATC) system will produce enormous \nenvironmental and economic benefits, and American supports efforts to modernize our ATC system. We encourage \npolicymakers to advance policies that achieve that objective, and we are committed to working with the FAA and \nother policymakers to make it a reality. \n\nIn 2021, the FAA implemented more efficient descent procedures that will make a meaningful impact in reducing \nfuel use and associated CO2 emissions. American supported designing the new procedures by providing technical \ndata and expertise on aircraft behavior and systems, energy management considerations and application. The new \nOptimized Profile Descents allow planes to glide down safely from cruising altitudes into airspace around some of \nthe nations largest airports, instead of the traditional stair-step procedure that consumes more fuel. For each group \nof descents used at an airport, the FAA estimates that an average of 2 million gallons of fuel is saved, and 18,000 \nmetric tons of CO2 emissions are reduced annually.* \nAmerican has also partnered with the FAA and NASA on a trial program in Charlotte, North Carolina, to test \nand validate the benefits of Terminal Flight Data Manager infrastructure. During testing at Charlotte Douglas \nInternational Airport, the program reduced taxi times, helping to save more than 275,000 gallons of fuel annually. \nThe program also avoided almost eight tons of CO2 emissions daily and cut delays by 916 hours over four years, \nequivalent to an average of 15 minutes of wait time on a taxiway for more than 3,600 departing flights.** In 2021, \nNASA transferred findings from the trial program to the FAA for nationwide implementation.\n\n*  https://www.faa.gov/newsroom/faa-implements-more-efficient-descent-procedures-reduce-fuel-burn-emissions.\n** https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-transfers-air-traffic-management-tool-updates-to-faa.\n\n  Reducing excess weight. The weight on an aircraft is a \ncritical driver of how much fuel it uses, and even small \nreductions in weight can add up to significant fuel and \nGHG emissions savings when multiplied across our whole \nfleet and the many flights each aircraft makes. \nWe have taken a number of steps to reduce weight on \nour aircraft, including installing lighter seats, removing \nseat-back entertainment systems, discontinuing American \nWay magazine, and stocking our galleys with only as \nmuch ice as we expect passengers will use on each flight. \nEven using lighter paint makes a difference: On our A321 \nfleet alone, this saves about 1 million gallons of fuel per \nyear. Collectively, our weight-reduction efforts save 12.4 \nmillion gallons of fuel annually, which equals 117,800 \nmillion metric tons of CO2 emissions avoided each year. \n\n  Optimizing flight plans and procedures. We focus on \nflying as efficiently as possible, which includes consid-\nering everything from the speed and paths our aircraft \ntake on departure and descent to how flight crews adjust \nen route to account for changing weather conditions.\nSince we began deploying specialized software in 2020 \nthat uses real-time weather conditions to provide our \nflight crews with better data about optimal flight altitudes \nand speeds, we have saved more than 8.4 million gallons \nof fuel. That translates to just over 80,000 metric tons of \nCO2 emissions avoided. This and other flight planning \nimprovements also help us optimize the amount of arrival \nfuel on the aircraft  that is, the extra fuel carried on \nthe aircraft  which makes a big difference in reducing \nweight and, therefore, improving fuel efficiency. \n\n16\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nSustainable Aviation Fuel\nThe clearest near-term way for us to decarbonize is by using \nSAF, which is why purchasing and helping scale SAF produc-\ntion is the cornerstone of our climate strategy this decade. \nSAF will also be key to achieving the in-sector reductions \nrequired to meet our science-based target for 2035. \n\nIn late 2021, we finalized a new SAF offtake agreement with \nAemetis, an advanced renewable fuels and biochemicals \ncompany, to take delivery of 16 million gallons of Aemetis \n\nSAF annually over a seven-year period beginning in 2024. \nThe agreement is the result of work with the oneworld \nAlliance. (See box at right.) The SAF will be produced at \nthe Aemetis Carbon Zero plant under development in \nRiverbank, California. The facility will use zero carbon \nintensity hydroelectric electricity to process nonedible \nwaste oils into SAF. Emissions associated with the SAF will \nbe further reduced by producing hydrogen, which is used \nin SAF processing, from waste wood and by capturing and \nsequestering any remaining CO2 underground.\n\nPETROLEUM-BASED JET FUEL*\n\nSUSTAINABLE AVIATION FUEL*\n\nThe combustion of jet \nfuel releases CO2e into \n\nthe atmosphere\n+73g CO2e/MJ\n\nThe combustion of \njet fuel releases CO2e \ninto the atmosphere\n\n+73g CO2e/MJ\n\n+89gCO2e/MJ* \n\nLIFE CYCLE EMISSIONS \nFROM CONVENTIONAL \n\nJET FUEL\n\n60%80% \n\nFEWER LIFE CYCLE EMISSIONS \n\nFROM SAF THAN FROM  \nCONVENTIONAL JET FUEL\n\nCrude oil extraction  \nand refining releases  \n\nCO2e emissions\n+16g CO2e/MJ\n\nEmissions from renewable  \n\nhydrocarbon feedstock  \ncollection, transportation  \n\nand refining\n+22.5g CO2e/MJ\n\nPlants absorb carbon \n\nin the air through \nphotosynthesis\n73g CO2e/MJ\n\n*   Emissions data are averages, based on estimates from LCA of Current & Future GHG Emissions from Petroleum Jet Fuel, Massachusetts Institute of Technology Laboratory for Aviation \n\nand the Environment. CO2e per megajoule (MJ) is a measure of GHG emissions per unit of energy.\n\nAdvancing SAF Through the oneworld Alliance\nThe members of the oneworld Alliance  which \nincludes American and 12 other carriers  have \ntaken a number of important steps to chart a path \nforward in reducing their emissions. In September \n2020, oneworld became the first global airline \nalliance to announce a target of carbon neutrality by \n2050, establishing its commitment to sustainability. \nThe alliance followed up that commitment with an \nintermediate goal to achieve 10% SAF use across \nthe member airlines by 2030. This is not just about \nsetting a target, but also committing to playing an \nactive role in the development of SAF at commer-\ncial scale that is affordable, available and certified \nwith the sustainability criteria as recognized by the \nInternational Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) and \nrelevant authorities.\n\nIn late 2021 and early 2022, the oneworld Alliance \nairlines announced their intention to purchase up \nto 550 million gallons of blended SAF from the \nrenewable fuels companies Aemetis and Gevo for \ntheir operations at California airports. Once finalized, \nthe agreements will cover the delivery of SAF over a \nfive- to seven-year term beginning in 2024. The SAF is \nblended with petroleum jet fuel to meet international \nstandards for aviation fuel.\n\n17\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nThe agreement with Aemetis brings Americans total SAF \ncommitment to more than 120 million gallons. That includes \nplans to purchase up to 10 million gallons of carbon-neutral \nSAF produced by Prometheus Fuels, which uses a novel \nprocess to make net zero carbon transportation fuels. \nAmerican took our first delivery of SAF in mid-2020, and in \n2021 we used over 1.4 million gallons of SAF. That makes \nus the only member of Airlines for America to report using \nmore than 1 million gallons of SAF during the year. \n\nAs critical as SAF is for achieving our own and our industrys \nclimate goals, it is not yet available at the scale or price \nneeded to reduce emissions significantly. Scaling SAF produc-\ntion to the point where it can materially reduce aviations \nemissions and be cost competitive will take the combined \nefforts of the private and public sectors. One way American \nis helping advance those efforts is as an anchor partner \nin Breakthrough Energy Catalyst (see page 13). We also \ncontinue to advocate for governments to deploy policy tools, \nincluding incentives, credits and investments in research, \nto create the market conditions needed to make SAF an \neconomically viable alternative to conventional jet fuel. \n\nAnother way we are working to build the SAF market is by \npartnering with our corporate customers to simultaneously \nhelp advance their climate commitments while growing \ndemand for SAF. In early 2021, we launched an innovative \npilot program with Deloitte to explore how a new market-\nbased solution  a certificate that allocates the emissions \nreduction value of SAF  can benefit companies seeking \nto reduce their Scope 3 business travel emissions. The SAF \ncertificate is a concept under development by the World \nEconomic Forums Clean Skies for Tomorrow initiative, \naimed at unlocking new capital to boost SAF production  \nby harnessing the ambition of corporate climate goals. \n\nEnabling Our Customers to Offset Their Flights\nAmerican partners with Cool Effect, a leading nonprofit provider of carbon \noffsets, to give our customers the opportunity to easily calculate the \nemissions of their flight and purchase high-quality offsets. Thousands of \ncustomers have chosen to offset the emissions from their flights through \nCool Effect since we launched the program in 2020. Companies partic-\nipating in Americans Business Extra program can redeem their points \nwith Cool Effect to offset the carbon emissions of their business travel. \nAnd AAdvantage members can use their Loyalty Choice Rewards to \nredeem carbon offsets through Cool Effect as well.\n\nCool Effect uses more than 90% of each offset dollar to fund a portfolio of \nhigh-quality, verified carbon reduction projects that protect and conserve \nour planets resources. \n\nLearn more at www.cooleffect.org/american-airlines. \n\nThis agreement was one of the first collaborations between \nan organization seeking to reduce net emissions from \nbusiness travel and a U.S. airline that is using SAF in its \ndaily operations. We have since completed similar agree-\nments with Kuehne+Nagel, a global logistics company, \nBank of America, and a number of other companies.\n\nMarket-Based Measures\nMarket-based mechanisms such as carbon offsets are \na valuable tool for meeting the global climate challenge, \nbut reducing emissions through improved efficiency and \nincreased use of SAF are  and will remain  our priority. \nWhere necessary, though, we will purchase offsets.\n\nCORSIA regulates emissions from international aviation. \nWe have endorsed its goal of achieving carbon-neutral \ngrowth in emissions after 2019. Airlines and other aircraft \noperators will offset any growth in CO2 emissions above \nthe revised 2019 baseline established in the wake of the \nCOVID-19 pandemic. In 2021, American and other airlines \ndid not face offsetting obligations under CORSIA, as \ninternational flight volumes were still below pre-pandemic \nlevels. Going forward, Americans aim is to meet our \nCORSIA obligations by increasing our use of SAF, but  \nwe recognize offsets will also play a role.\n\n18\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Avoiding Contrails\nReducing the aviation industrys contribution to climate \nchange requires fully understanding and addressing all \nthe ways our industry currently impacts the climate. While \nthe GHG emissions of jet fuel use are well understood, \nthere is a growing focus on the effect of condensation \ntrails  known as contrails  the ice clouds that can form \nwhen a planes hot, humid exhaust mixes with cool, humid \nair high in the atmosphere.\n\nContrails change the climate in two ways: They stop the \nEarths heat from escaping from the atmosphere (warming \neffect) and they block the sun by reflecting incoming \nsunlight back into space (cooling effect). During the day, \ncontrails can cool the Earth, whereas they are warming at \nnight. (See accompanying illustration.) While there remains \nuncertainty about the precise magnitude of contrails \nclimate impact, there is an emerging scientific consensus \nthat the warming impact of contrails is dominant.\n\nGiven that, developing effective contrail avoidance \nstrategies must be part of the industrys net zero roadmap. \nAmerican recognizes that such strategies come with \ncompeting climate effects: Changing flight paths to avoid \ncontrail formation could increase fuel burn and associated \nGHG emissions. American is committed to helping advance \nunderstanding of this important climate issue  and to \ntaking action to address it within our own operations.\n\nCEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nLOWER FUEL BURN AND MAXIMUM ALLOWABLE ALTITUDE\n\nAltitude range that produces contrails \n\nin the right conditions \n\n(hot exhaust + cool humid air)\n\nHIGHER FUEL BURN\n\nHigh Heat Trapping\n\nLow Heat Trapping\n\n19\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nClimate-Related Risk Assessment\n\nSITE-LEVEL ANALYSIS OF PHYSICAL RISKS\n\nThrough our existing enterprisewide risk management \nprocess, American monitors and manages a broad range \nof strategic, financial and operational risks, including risks \nassociated with climate change. To inform our understanding \nof the climate risk landscape, in 2020 we conducted an initial \nforward-looking scenario analysis that focused on identifying \nand assessing the physical and transition climate-related \nrisks and opportunities facing the company over the short, \nmedium and long term. In 2022, we built on this by under-\ntaking a more detailed analysis of the risks and opportunities. \nThis included expanding the number of sites included in the \nphysical risk evaluation; exploring geographic regions around \nthe world in which we operate that are projected to experi-\nence greater impacts; examining more closely the effects of \npotential changes in policy, technologies and markets; and \nrefining and updating the scenarios we used to model and \nassess potential risks and opportunities. \n\nThe insights from this process, conducted in alignment with \nthe recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related \nFinancial Disclosures (TCFD), are directly informing our \nclimate strategy and updates to our pathway to net zero. \nThey are also building the foundation for more deeply \nintegrating climate risk analysis into our ongoing risk \nmanagement and business, strategy and financial planning \nprocesses. They were also used to facilitate conversations \nwith key internal stakeholders.\n\nPhysical Risk Assessment \nAs part of our expanded physical risk assessment, we \nconducted a climate risk screening in 2022 of approximately \n400 American Airlines facilities and suppliers, including \n\nLocation\n\nMIA\nMiami Int. For \neach of these sites, we assessed the risk associated with \ntemperature, coastal flooding, fluvial (river) flooding, tropical \ncyclones (Eastern Atlantic basin only), water stress, drought \nand wildfire.3 Our analysis was supported by The Climate \nService, a leading provider of climate science and analytics \nfor business.\n\nThe results of our analysis refined our focus on 12 strategi-\ncally important sites for our company, which include hub \nairports that form the foundation of our network; our largest \nmaintenance facility; our corporate headquarters, which is \nalso home to our integrated operations center and primary \ntraining facility; and a key fuel supplier. For each site, we \nassessed the exposure and implications of the projected \nkey physical hazards in the 2020s, 2030s and 2050s, based \non the scenarios used. Adaptive capacity refers to the resilience \nmeasures to manage climate-related impacts. We are taking \nthe results from the 2022 assessment and engaging key \nstakeholders across the company to discuss the identified \nrisks and how we can better prepare our assets.\n\nTransition Risks and Opportunities Assessment \nWe also deepened and refined our analysis of Americans \nexposure to transition risks related to climate change, \n\n3 \n\n American is reviewing the methodology for wildfire projections, which currently \ndo not account for land use or land cover. References to wildfire risk are therefore \nomitted from this report.\n\nClimate Scenarios\nScenario analysis is not a prediction or forecast of future \nevents but rather a tool to explore and highlight central \nelements of possible futures. American aligns with best \npractice in selecting the scenarios we use in our climate \nrisk assessment process. We use multiple scenarios, \nincluding a lower-emissions, below 2C scenario  \nconsistent with the ambition of the Paris Agreement in \nlimiting global warming to well below 2C  as well as \nan above 2C scenario.\n\nDue to the distinct nature of physical and transition \nrisks, standard practice is to use different scenarios for \nanalyzing the two different types of risks. For analysis \nof physical risk, we use Representative Concentration \nPathway (RCP) scenarios, as recommended by TCFD, \nwhich were developed for use in Intergovernmental \n\nPanel on Climate Change assessments. For analysis of \ntransition risk, we use the IEAs WEO STEPS and SDS \nscenarios. For our 2022 analysis, we used 2030 and 2050 \ntimeframes, consistent with our initial 2020 analysis. \n\nThe following are the scenarios we used: \n\nPHYSICAL RISKS\n\nTRANSITION RISKS\n\nLower emissions \nscenarios\n\nRCP4.5\n\nIEA 2021 WEO Sustainable \nDevelopment Scenario (SDS)\n\nWarming \nprojections\n\n1.73.2C by 2100\n\nHigher emissions \nscenarios\n\nRCP8.5\n\nApproximately 1.7C by  \n2050 (peak) then declines\n\nIEA 2021 WEO Stated  \nPolicies Scenario (STEPS)\n\nWarming \nprojections\n\n3.25.4C by 2100\n\nApproximately 2.6C by 2100\n\nincluding the policy and legal, technology, market, reputation \nand operational risks  as well as opportunities  that \ncould arise from the transition to a low-carbon or carbon-\nconstrained economy.\n\nFor the lower- and higher-emissions scenarios considered, \nwe used the International Energy Agency (IEA) 2021 World \nEnergy Outlook (WEO) Stated Policies Scenario (STEPS) and \nSustainable Development Scenario (SDS) as the primary lens \nfor the transition risk and opportunity assessment. Transition \nscenarios compare different possible versions of the future \nand the levers and actions that produce them, with the aim \n\nof stimulating insights about the future of global energy. The \nIEA notes that decisions made by governments are the main \ndifferentiating factor explaining the variations in outcomes \nacross the scenarios, but they also account for the economic \nand demographic context, technology costs and learning, \nenergy prices and affordability, corporate sustainability \ncommitments, and social and behavioral factors. \n\nThe table that starts on the following page summarizes the \nkey transition risks and opportunities identified, along with \nAmericans mitigation strategies.\n\n21\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nANALYSIS OF CLIMATE-RELATED RISKS AND OPPORTUNITIES\n\nTransition Risk and Opportunities\nPhysical Risk\n\nSHORT TERM: 02 yrs\nSHORT TERM: 2020s\n\nMEDIUM TERM: 315 yrs\nMEDIUM TERM: 2030s\n\nLONG TERM: 1630 yrs\nLONG TERM: 2050s\n\nPotential Financial Impact Level\n\nlow\n\n \n\nmed\n\n \n\nhigh\n\nRisk Type\n\nPolicy  \nand legal\n\nClimate-Related  \nRisk Definition\n\nThe risk from existing and \nemerging regulation aimed at \naddressing climate change. \nThis might include: \n  Increased pricing of GHG \n\nemissions\n\n  Enhanced reporting \n\nobligations\n\n  Exposure to litigation\n  Limits on a license to \n\noperate\n\n \n\ns\nk\ns\ni\nR\nn\no\ni\nt\ni\ns\nn\na\nr\nT\n\nTechnology  The risk from emerging tech-\nnologies aimed at supporting \nthe global low-carbon transi-\ntion. They could also mandate  \nnew technologies that would impose significant capital and \noperating costs on us.\n\nOur fleet renewal program gives us the youngest fleet among \nU.S. network carriers; however, more aggressive emission \nconstraints imposed in the near to medium term may place us \nat a disadvantage to competitors who are beginning to upgrade \ntheir fleets to the most recent generation of aircraft.\nThe emerging focus on hydrogen propulsion system modifica-\ntions for regional aircraft may reduce investment in the next \ngeneration of conventionally powered regional jets, which \ncould improve efficiency by more than 15%.\nThere is a risk that technology does not develop sufficiently to \nallow us to also meet our ambitious climate goals.\n\nWe are developing a robust and multifaceted long-term climate \nchange strategy aimed at driving progress toward ambitious goals \nand positioning our company to be a leader on sustainability. \nWe monitor emerging regulations around the world to understand \nthe risks and opportunities for our business. And we work with \npolicymakers to identify policy solutions that can help the aviation \nindustry reduce its emissions through new technologies. We also \ncontinue to advocate for CORSIA as the single global approach to \naddressing emissions from international aviation. \nWe continue to seek efficiency gains in our operations, pursue \nopportunities to employ SAF and seek to employ lower-emission \nor zero-emission technologies as they become available on a \ncommercially reasonable basis.\n\nSince 2013, we have undertaken an extensive fleet replacement \ninitiative, taking delivery of more than 600 new, more fuel-efficient \naircraft  including the Boeing 737 MAX, the Airbus A321neo and \nthe Boeing 787 Dreamliner  which are among the most fuel- \nefficient aircraft on the market. Over the same period, we retired  \na similar number of older, less fuel-efficient aircraft. As of year-end \n2021, American continues to have the youngest mainline fleet of \nany U.S. network airline, with an average age of 11.3 years and \n55% of our mainline aircraft being less than 10 years old. \nTo accelerate private sector action, in September 2021, we became \nan anchor partner to Breakthrough Energy Catalyst. American \ncommitted to invest $100 million in an innovative collaborative \neffort to advance a set of clean energy technologies that are \ncritical to a zero-carbon economy but are currently more \nexpensive than their existing fossil-fuel counterparts. Catalyst \nand its partners will work together to finance and produce new \nsolutions in four technologies: SAF, green hydrogen, long-duration \nenergy storage and direct air capture.\n\n22\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nClimate-Related  \nRisk Definition\n\nPotential Financial Impact\n\nShort  \nTerm\n\nMedium  \n\nTerm\n\nLong  \nTerm\n\nMitigation Strategy\n\nPotential Financial Impact Level\n\nlow\n\n \n\nmed\n\n \n\nhigh\n\nRisk Type\n\nMarket\n\nThe risk from shifting supply \nand demand as economies \nreact to climate change. We intend to further integrate other sustainability \npractices into the products, services and experiences we offer \nour customers. \nWe are testing new ways to expand our network and reduce \nemissions. In 2022, we introduced premium motorcoach \nservice to connect our customers in three Pennsylvania \nmarkets to Philadelphia International Airport  increasing \nconvenience for our passengers while helping take individual \ncars off the road. \n\nWe are positioning our company to be a leader on sustainability \nby implementing a robust and multifaceted climate change \nstrategy aimed at driving progress toward our ambitious \nclimate goals, including our 2035 SBTi target and long-term  \nnet zero 2050 goal.\nWe intend to continue our efforts to reduce carbon emissions \nusing the various levers available to us at this time  including \nconsideration of how to include modern aircraft, efficient tech-\nnology, sound operational practices and sustainable fuels  in \nour climate mitigation strategy. We are looking to embrace new \nlow-carbon levers as they become available.\nWe continue to communicate our sustainability practices to our \ncustomers, team members and suppliers so they understand \nthe measures we are taking to reduce our climate impact. \nWe also regularly solicit feedback from these stakeholders to \ninform our efforts. \n\n23\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Risk Type\n\nAcute\n\nClimate-Related  \nRisk Definition\n\nThe risk of increasing severity \nof weather events\n\ns\nk\ns\ni\nR\n\n \nl\n\na\nc\n\ni\ns\ny\nh\nP\n\nCEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nPotential Financial Impact\n\nShort  \nTerm\n\nMedium  \n\nTerm\n\nLong  \nTerm\n\nMitigation Strategy\n\nPotential Financial Impact Level\n\nlow\n\n \n\nmed\n\n \n\nhigh\n\nExtremely high temperatures may exceed the maximum \nallowable temperature at which our aircraft are certified by the \nFAA to operate.\n\nIncreases in hot days can interrupt our operations by causing \nheat buckling on runways and taxiways and other infrastructure \ndamage. Such damage in turn can increase operational and repair \ncosts for airports  costs that would be passed through to us.\n\nIn extreme cases, it may become difficult to cool aircraft to an \nacceptable temperature for customers and crew.\n\nIncreased frequency and intensity of hurricanes places opera-\ntions and infrastructure at Miami International Airport at risk. \nIncreases in storm activities can result in substantial costs \nrelating to canceled flights and airport closures.\n\nFlooding from intense precipitation at major hubs in Charlotte, \nNorth Carolina, Los Angeles and London can interrupt critical \nexpansion strategies. Increases in precipitation can result in \nexcess loading of stormwater infrastructure designed for lesser \nflows, increasing the risk of flooding. Increases in the severity of \nstorms can cause flooding, which can wear infrastructure.\n\nCyclonic events in the Gulf of Mexico region  where almost 50% \nof U.S. crude oil refining capacity is located  can disrupt fuel \nsupplies. A significant portion of our fuel is sourced from Gulf of \nMexico refineries and is stored in, or must be transported from, the \nregion, which poses a risk to our operations if those facilities are \ndisabled for any period of time. Pipelines and storage terminals may \nalso be at risk from extreme weather. Terminals may be supplied via \nocean-going vessels if refineries are shut down, but there are no \nviable alternatives to move the amount of fuel stranded if pipelines \nare shut down due to flooding or other hurricane impacts.\n\nWe continue to monitor temperatures at airports exposed to \nacute temperature risk and work with aircraft manufacturers to \nensure that our aircraft are able to operate safely under a range \nof operational conditions. \nOver the next five years, we intend to incorporate the projected \nimpacts of climate change into design standards for physical \nassets, capital improvement plans, disaster management, \nemergency response and scheduling.\nTo mitigate projected impacts from increasing temperatures, we \nplan to invest in additional ground cooling and upgrades to gate-\nbased cooling systems.\n\nWe are investigating options to mitigate the impacts of hurri-\ncanes, which may include enhancing airport infrastructure to \nwithstand stronger winds from storms. \n\nTo mitigate the impact of flooding on infrastructure, we plan \nto incorporate the projected impact of increasing precipitation \ninto design standards for physical assets, capital improvement \nplans, disaster management and emergency response, master \nplan development and early warning systems.\n\nOur strategies to mitigate this risk include sourcing our fuel \nfrom multiple regions and maintaining a reserve of fuel at our \nhub airports. The number of days of operations held in these \nreserves varies by airport, depending on the risk of extreme \nweather, the number of pipelines that serve the airport and \nother factors. We monitor closely the changing likelihood of \nsevere weather and adjust these reserves accordingly.\nAnother strategy to mitigate this risk is our work to expand \nthe commercial availability of SAF, which has the potential to \nfurther diversify fuel sources and supply.\n\n24\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Risk Type\n\nChronic\n\nClimate-Related  \nRisk Definition\n\nThe risk of longer-term \nchanges in weather patterns\n\ns\nk\ns\ni\nR\n\n \nl\n\na\nc\n\ni\ns\ny\nh\nP\n\nCEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nPotential Financial Impact\n\nShort  \nTerm\n\nMedium  \n\nTerm\n\nLong  \nTerm\n\nMitigation Strategy\n\nPotential Financial Impact Level\n\nlow\n\n \n\nmed\n\n \n\nhigh\n\nSea-level rise in Miami, Los Angeles, Philadelphia and New \nYork may require hardening of the airports in these locations, or \neven relocation.\n\nBecause high air temperatures reduce air density, chronically \nhigh temperatures at some of our hub airports may require \nrestricting the availability of seats for sale in certain markets, the \nuse of aircraft with higher engine thrust and potentially reduced \nschedules. \n\nGiven the vulnerability of these key airports to flooding from \nsea-level rise, and the resulting impact to business continuity, \nwe intend to investigate options to mitigate the impacts of \nsea-level rise, which may include fortifying the shoreline around \nthose facilities and, as a last resort, considering options for \nrelocation to areas further inland. The cost/benefit of available \noptions may lead to adjustments to our network. We also plan \nto engage with policymakers and airport authorities to explore \npaths to greater resiliency. \n\nOver the next five years, we plan to incorporate the projected \nimpacts of climate change into aircraft purchasing plans, routing \nand scheduling.
