Airlines certified \nunder IEnvA standards will also be ISO 14001 certified.\n\nOperating sustainably in our facilities \nAs part of our goal to source 2.5 million GJs of cost- \ncompetitive renewable energy to power our operations \nby 2025, we purchased nearly 750,000 GJs of electricity \nfrom renewable sources for our headquarters facilities and \noperations at DFW in 2021. In the past year, these facilities \nwere 100% powered by renewable energy. As of January \n2022, American was the highest-ranked transportation \ncompany  and 53rd overall  on the U.S. Environmental \nProtection Agencys Green Power Partnership Fortune \n500 Partners List.4 \n\n4 \n\n https://www.epa.gov/system/files/documents/2022-04/fortune500_jan2022.pdf.\n\nAmerican Airlines headquarters  \nin Fort Worth, Texas\n\nWe also have multiple LEED Gold- and Silver-certified \nfacilities across the United States, including two LEED \nGold-certified buildings at our corporate headquarters \ncampus that we opened in 2019.\n\nReducing environmental impacts on board\nAmerican has a number of longtime efforts aimed at \nreducing waste and increasing recycling on board our \naircraft. Among them, American recycles an average of \nabout 21,000 pounds of aluminum cans annually through \nour flight services. \n\n27\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nReducing Aircraft Noise\nWe recognize and are committed to addressing the \nongoing concerns of local communities regarding \naircraft noise. One way we have done this over \nthe past few years is by voluntarily retrofitting our \naircraft with fuel vent vortex generators (VGs). These \nfairings are installed around the wing fuel tank over \nthe pressure vent, on the underside of the wing \nof the A320 family of aircraft. These vents reduce \nairframe noise during portions of the approach by an \nestimated four to six decibels. Prior to 2014 deliveries, \nAirbus did not equip aircraft with VGs  so American \nhas invested over $1 million to retrofit our pre-2014 \naircraft with this feature.\n\nBy April 2022, we had modified 290 narrowbody \npre-2014 aircraft with retrofit VGs, meaning all Airbus \naircraft in our fleet now have the VGs utility.\n\nWe also continue to meet or exceed ICAO noise \ncertification standards, which currently specify that \noperators can fly Stage 3, Stage 4 or Stage 5 aircraft. \nAll of Americans mainline and regional fleet meet \nStage 4 noise certification levels, and 20% meet \nStage 5 noise certification levels. \n\nWe are also taking steps to use more sustainable \nmaterials  and, in particular, to find ways to reduce \nsingle-use plastics  as part of our onboard products \nand meal service. While adjustments made in response to \nCOVID-19 presented challenges in advancing some of our \nsustainable materials goals  such as providing bottles of \nwater rather than refilling cups to minimize contact  we \nhave tested a number of new products over the past two \nyears that we are aiming to roll out more broadly. \n\nFor example, in 2021 we piloted a sustainable cutlery kit \nmade out of bamboo. We also began offering a sustainable \nmeal box, which is a fully compostable box with prepack-\naged snacks, across our regional operations. In addition, \nwe introduced new onboard amenity kits for premium \ncabin customers in partnership with Shinola and D.S. & \nDurga, which include a number of sustainability features. \nFor example, the dental kit and ear plugs are individually \npackaged within a biodegradable wax paper instead of \nsingle-use plastic, and the toothbrush is made from wheat \nstraw instead of plastic.\n\nAlongside these onboard efforts, we have instituted a \nnumber of sustainability improvements in our lounges. \nThey include switching from plastic to compostable \nflatware and straws, installing water bottle filler stations, \ntesting reusable to-go bags and more. \n\nFor detailed performance data related to energy use, \nGHG and other air emissions, waste, water, noise \nand other environmental topics, see page 55.\n\n28\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##OPERATING SAFELY\n\nCEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nAmerican aspires to be nothing less than the safest airline in the world  for our customers and \nour workforce. Even as we dealt with a second full year of COVID-19, this mission remained our \ntop priority. We were proud to safely transport over 165 million customers in 2021, more than any \nother U.S. carrier. \n\nTo ensure that we operate every flight safely and protect \nour people, we insist on a culture where all team members \nbelieve they can personally drive our safety efforts. Every \nteam member who touches our aircraft is empowered to \ntake a plane out of service if they have a safety concern. And \nwe continue to expand a culture that encourages all team \nmembers and contractors to ask questions and report safety \nhazards, concerns and incidents without fear of reprisal.\n\nSafety Governance and Management\n\nAn uncompromising commitment to safety, security and \ncontinuous improvement is a shared responsibility  from \nour Board of Directors to frontline team members. Our \nChief Executive Officer retains ultimate responsibility and \nauthority for safety culture and performance, while the \nBoards Corporate Governance, Public Responsibility and \nSafety Committee has formal oversight responsibilities for \nsafety. Additionally, the Board receives monthly updates \non key safety performance metrics and multiple detailed \nreviews throughout the year.\n\nReorganizing our safety group\nFlying is already the safest transportation industry in the \nworld, but we continually seek ways of further elevating \n\nour safety efforts. As part of this process, we reorganized \nour safety team in 2021 to create cross-departmental \ncenters of excellence designed to drive a more consistent, \nunified approach to addressing risk and compliance \nacross the company. As a result, our safety group is now \norganized into the following three teams:\n  Safety Systems Engineering and Safety Science is \n\nresponsible for creating proactive and predictive strat-\negies based on the high reliability organization (HRO) \nmodel (see accompanying box). This team includes \nFatigue Risk Management, the Safety Management \nSystem, Emergency Planning and Response, Safety \nScience, Safety System Design and Resiliency, and Safety \nTechnology and Analytics.\n\n  Compliance and Auditing is responsible for managing \n\nreactive daily air and ground operational concerns tacti-\ncally, managing safety audits and proactively engaging \nwith our regulators to enhance collaboration and relation-\nships. This team includes Regulatory Compliance, Internal \nEvaluation Program, Environmental, Dangerous Goods/\nHazmat and Employee Safety and Health programs. \n\n  Safety, Efficiency and Continuous Improvement is \n\ndesigned to analyze and react to data sourced from \ninvestigations, compliance reporting, safety reporting \nand safety programs to continuously improve on current \nprocesses and grow Americans safety culture.\n\nAdopting the High Reliability Organization Model\nAmerican has adopted the HRO model as part of \nour safety efforts because HROs have demonstrated \nsuccess in hazardous industries, maintaining  \nsafe work standards despite environmental and \norganizational complexity. HROs exhibit and value  \nthe following five principles:\n  Commitment to resilience\n  Preoccupation with failure\n  Sensitivity to operations\n  Deference to expertise\n  Reluctance to simplify\n\n30\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021OPERATING SAFELY\\\\ Safety\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Our Safety Management System\n\nThe safety of our customers and team members is guided \nby our Safety Management System (SMS), an organization-\nwide approach to identifying and managing risk. American \nwas the first U.S. carrier to pioneer SMS in 2009. It has since \nbeen incorporated into Federal Aviation Administration \n(FAA) regulations for all carriers. \n\nOur SMS emphasizes safety management as a funda-\nmental business process across the enterprise. It involves \na full commitment from the most senior leaders through \nto each team member to integrate safety into how we do \nour jobs. Our SMS promotes a culture in which our team \nmembers proactively identify, analyze and mitigate risks. \nThe SMS ensures robust and repeatable processes with \nlocal ownership, driven by data to reduce risks and contin-\nuously improve and enhance safety. We collaborate closely \nwith the FAA to maintain operational safety at the highest \nlevel possible and actively share best practices with our \nindustry peers, governments and aerospace manufac-\nturers. The four components of our SMS are noted in the \naccompanying box.\n\nSafety Policy\nOur corporate Safety Policy applies to all team members, \nbusiness partners, contractors and consultants. It sets \nAmericans safety objectives and standards and assigns \nresponsibilities for safety across our organization. The \npolicy also conveys managements commitment to safety \nperformance and to improving the level of safety through \nmeasurable goals and key performance indicators. Part of \nour SMS foundation, this policy helps to create a culture \n\nCEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nOUR SAFETY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM\n\n1 Safety  \n\nPolicy\n\nEstablishes senior \nmanagements commitment \nto continually improve \nsafety; defines the methods, \nprocesses and organizational \nstructure needed to meet goals\n\n2 Safety  \n\nAssurance 3 Safety Risk \n\nManagement 4 Safety \n\nPromotion\n\nEvaluates the continued \neffectiveness of implemented \nrisk control strategies; \nsupports the identification  \nof new hazards\n\nDetermines the need for,  \nand adequacy of, new revised \nrisk controls, based on the \nassessment of acceptable risk\n\nIncludes training, \ncommunication and other \nactions to create a positive \nsafety culture within  \nall levels of the workforce\n\nthat encourages effective management of risk along with \ncontinuous improvement. The Safety Policy complies with \nall applicable regulatory requirements and laws in the \ncountries where we operate and establishes standards for \nacceptable operational behaviors. \n\nOur Emergency Response Manual (ERM), which establishes \neffective and efficient response practices for various types \nof emergencies, is an integral part of our SMS. The ERM \nserves as the governing document for the American Airlines \nCorporate Emergency Response Plan. It includes guidelines \nto prepare for and respond to emergencies, responsibilities \nfor team members, protocols for communicating with internal \nand external stakeholders and mechanisms to report \nemergencies. The ERM also includes a detailed Pandemic \n\nPreparedness and Response Plan that helped us navigate \nthrough every phase of the COVID-19 pandemic.\n\nSafety Assurance\nThe Safety Assurance component of our SMS stipulates how \nwe use data and conduct quality assurance and internal \noversight to validate the effectiveness of risk controls and \nthe performance of the SMS. Composed of several individual \nprograms and initiatives, Safety Assurance verifies that risk \ncontrols in our operational processes continue to conform \nto requirements and remain effective in maintaining risks at \nacceptable levels.\n\n31\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021OPERATING SAFELY\\\\ Safety\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nSafety Reporting\nOur senior leadership team, which includes our Chief \nExecutive Officer and Chief Operating Officer, receives \nmonthly updates on team member safety and risks across \nour system. We focus on injury reduction, evaluate trends and \ndevelop programs to enhance safety. We are centralizing our \ndata collection and injury reporting tools to provide better \nvisibility, simplicity and easy access for company leaders. In \naddition to monitoring injury rates, we closely track aircraft \nground damage, both as a part of our safety culture and \nbecause it is correlated with on-the-job injuries. \nAfter a significant decline from 2019 to 2020, team member \ninjury rates in our mainline and regional operations rose \nalong with the increase in our operations in 2021. The \nchallenges associated with ramping up our operations \nas demand returned and introducing new and returning \nteam members back into our operations contributed to \nthis increase. We remain focused on reducing injuries and \nredoubling our efforts to enhance our health and safety \npolicies and procedures and elevate our safety culture. In \n2021, we also experienced an increase in accidents in our \nmainline operations; five of the six recorded accidents were \ndue to turbulence that caused crewmember injuries. As a \nresult, we are implementing new technologies that pilots \ncan use while en route to identify upcoming turbulence, \nupdating flight attendant procedures for anticipated and \nforecasted turbulence, and expanding our use of data \nanalysis by our Turbulence Task Force.\nThe overall goal of team member reporting is to improve \nsafety awareness and identify operational deficiencies by \nfacilitating an open line of communication between the \nemployees and management without fear of reprisal. Potential \nsafety concerns and suggestions identified through our many \n\nsafety reporting programs are critical to early identification of \nhazards. These reports also allow the company to proactively \naddress potential risks and implement corrective actions to \nresolve safety and security issues.\nWhen a team member identifies any safety-related concern, \nhe or she is encouraged to report the issue. Once the \nconcern is received, skilled safety investigators collaborate \nwith operational partners to review the information provided, \nassess the hazard and develop corrective actions to ensure \nthe issue is addressed. These reports are then reviewed as \npart of the broader SMS to determine if there are system- \nrelated risks developing. We follow up with the reporter to \ncommunicate what we learned and what steps we are taking \nto prevent similar concerns from arising again. This follow-\nthrough and prompt action helps encourage additional \nreporting, thus creating a robust safety reporting life cycle.\nOur most prominent safety reporting initiatives include the \nfollowing: Aviation Safety Action Programs, Ground Safety \nAction Programs, Flight Operations Quality Assurance, the \nInternational Air Transport Associations Operational Safety \nAudit, Line Operations Safety Audits, and the Learning and \nImprovement Team.\n\nSafety Action Programs\nEveryone at American has a role to perform in ensuring that \nour people, customers and assets remain safe. Through \nAviation Safety Action Programs (ASAPs) and Ground Safety \nAction Programs (GSAPs), team members can openly report \npotential hazards without concern of fault, thus improving \nour operations along the way. \nAmerican was the first airline to create an ASAP, although \nsuch programs are now commonplace among airlines \nworldwide. Currently, we have ASAPs for our Flight, Flight \n\n32\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021OPERATING SAFELY\\\\ Safety\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nService, Dispatch, Technical Operations and Central Load \nPlanning teams, giving us significantly greater coverage \nthan the industry average. In 2021, we recorded 10,847 \nASAP reports. We expect to roll out programs in 2022 for \nGate Agent and Crew Scheduling teams, which will give us \nASAP coverage across 100% of our operations. \n\nOur GSAP for Fleet Service and Cargo teams plays the same \nrole, encouraging team members to report potential safety \nissues in cargo and catering environments, control centers \nand on the ramp. This program was created in collaboration \nwith the Transport Workers Union of AmericaInternational \nAssociation of Machinists & Aerospace Workers and the \nFAA. In 2021, we recorded 487 GSAP reports.\n\nFlight Operations Quality Assurance (FOQA)\nFOQA is a voluntary safety program administered jointly \nby American and the Allied Pilots Association (APA) \nthat uses routinely recorded flight data to proactively \nidentify and correct deficiencies in flight operations. We \nroutinely monitor approximately 90% of our flights and use \nalgorithms to look for potential safety risks. The results help \nus better understand pilot performance and the operating \nenvironment. They also allow us to monitor aircraft systems, \nperformance and operational efficiency. \n\nTo enhance FOQAs effectiveness, American partnered \nwith Collins Aerospace in 2021 to retrofit our narrowbody \naircraft with its Aircraft Interface Device (AID). The entire \nfleet at American will be equipped with this wireless data \ntransfer system by the end of 2024. AID improves the speed \nwith which we can retrieve FOQA data, and it represents \nan important step toward increasing accuracy in monthly \nreporting, improving aircraft reliability and preparing for \nfuture products and capabilities. \n\nAmerican will also be the first carrier in the United States \nto adopt CEFA Aviation Mobile Services, a cloud-based \napplication that allows pilots to recreate their flights on their \ncompany iPad. This tool will improve on the concept of crew \ndebriefing by providing real-time feedback to our pilots. \nIt turns each flight into a learning opportunity, ultimately \ncontributing to the safety assurance of our SMS.\n\nInternational Air Transport Associations Operational Safety \nAudit (IOSA) \nAs part of our commitment to transparency and monitoring, \nwe are a registered participant in the IOSA program, which \nis an internationally recognized evaluation system designed \nto assess an airlines operational management and control \nsystems. An IOSA, which takes place every two years, creates \na structured methodology with standardized checklists \nthat are comparable on a worldwide basis, enabling and \nmaximizing the joint use of audit reports. In April 2022, we \nsuccessfully completed our IOSA audit in conformance with all \nstandards and recommended practices. As a result, American \nAirlines IOSA registration has been renewed until July 2024.\n\nLine Operations Safety Audits (LOSA)\nSince launching our continuous pilot LOSA program in 2017, \nwe have been sending highly trained pilot observers onto \nthe flight deck to better understand work-as-done versus \nwork-as-imagined. Observing our frontline team members in \naction and gathering safety-related data on environmental \nconditions, operational complexities and crew performance \nin real time provides us with valuable insights for enhancing \nsafety and resilience. \nWe are expanding LOSA to other work groups outside our \npilot group. In 2021, we implemented a continuous Dispatch \nLOSA and are collecting data to enhance safety performance.  \n\n The Learning and Improvement Team is the \nlatest addition to our Flight SMS programs. By \nfocusing on what we do well, it complements the \nprograms that concentrate primarily on areas \nwhere we need to improve.\n  Bobbi Wells\n\nVice President, Safety Systems, Efficiency and Compliance\n\nWe also are developing a Cabin LOSA program and expect \nto start conducting observations in 2023. The Cabin LOSA \nprogram will help us better understand the challenges facing \nour flight attendants and the measures we can take to keep \nthe cabin safe for everyone. We will continue to evaluate the \nfeasibility of expanding LOSA to other operational groups, \nwith 100% coverage as our ultimate goal.\n\nLearning and Improvement Team (LIT)\nWe created LIT in 2022 to collect and analyze data on what \nmakes our pilots successful in their everyday work. LIT is \ncomposed of line pilots who are specially trained in flight deck \nobservations and facilitated discussions. While it is similar in \nsome ways to LOSA, LIT is a separate program. One of the \nkey differences between LIT and Americans other Flight SMS \nprograms (i.e., ASAP, FOQA, LOSA) is that LIT focuses on what \ngoes well and why, thus providing a new safety lens through \nwhich to view the operation. Combining LIT data with other \nSMS data provides American with a broader picture of the \nsystem, rather than looking solely at unwanted outcomes.\n\n33\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021OPERATING SAFELY\\\\ Safety\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nEfficiency and Continuous  \nImprovement Team\nLearning and continuous \nimprovement are essential to \na robust safety program. This \nnew team at American will \nsolicit input and suggestions \nfrom frontline operational \nemployees on how to improve \nthe efficiency of the operation \nwithout compromising safety. \nDeferring to the expertise and \ninput from these employees, \nall ideas and suggestions \nwill be reviewed and vetted \n\nthrough our formalized SMS process. Employees may \nsubmit feedback and suggestions through their safety \nreporting programs, directly by email or by scanning the \nQR code on a card that is handed out during efficiency and \nsafety meetings and posted in select locations.\n\nSafety Risk Management\nThe Safety Risk Management (SRM) element of our SMS \nprovides a decision-making process for identifying hazards \nand mitigating risk based on a thorough understanding of \nour systems and their operating environment. SRM enables \nus to consider the risks in our operations and reduce them \nto an acceptable level. We use the SRM process whenever \nthere is a significant change to our operations, such as \ndelivery of a new type of aircraft or the addition of a new \nairport to our network. We also apply SRM when our Safety \nAssurance process identifies a new hazard or an ineffective \ncontrol of an existing hazard.\n\nWe use several tools to identify hazards and evaluate the \nneed for new or revised risk controls. The process of risk \nmanagement is the same regardless of the trigger or event, \nand our SMS looks at multiple factors for risk. While the \nFAA requirements are geared toward flight safety, our \nSMS goes further to evaluate a wider range of global risks, \nincluding operational disruptions. \n\nSafety Promotion\nSafety culture is the foundation of any SMS, with trust at the \ncore. At American we believe in a Just Culture approach, \nwhich encourages each team member to take responsibility \nand have accountability for achieving the highest safety \nstandards and results. This approach, which we have \nchampioned for more than a decade and has since become \nan accepted aviation industry standard, encourages team \nmembers to report errors, risky decisions or omissions \nwithout fear of punitive actions. We train our teams to look \nat potential safety events using three types of behaviors: \nhuman errors, at-risk behavior and reckless behavior. \n\nSafety Training\nOur ramp agents have the highest rate of injuries among \nall team member groups, primarily as the result of lifting \nbaggage, often in awkward and tight spaces. Working \nwith Pristine Condition International, which introduced \nthe science of Olympic weightlifting techniques to \nindustry, we recently conducted a training program on \nproper lifting techniques. This initiative included bringing \nathletic trainers to our busiest airport hubs to work with \nramp agents on body mechanics and fitness. Our flight \nattendant group has the second-highest rate of injuries, \nfollowed by aircraft mechanics, and we have initiatives \n\nunderway to reduce these rates as well. For example, \nwe produced three new seatbelt safety videos for team \nmembers based on actual incidents.\n\nTurbulence Task Force\nIn 2021, our Turbulence Task Force completed serving its \noriginal charter to reduce flight attendant and passenger \ninjuries during flight, and now the identified hazards and \nconcerns are addressed in our established and approved \nSMS process. The program proved highly successful. \n\nStaySafe and Safety Engagement Tool\nStaySafe is a safety communications campaign implemented \nacross our airport and technical operations organizations. \nIts materials focus on lessons learned and ways to prevent \nteam member injuries and equipment damage. Any bulletins \nor alerts are available across multiple platforms in order to \nreach all team members.\n\nThrough our new Safety Engagement Tool, we are bringing \ncompany leadership to the frontlines to engage in conver-\nsations with team members. Managers can communicate \nsafety expectations, assess risks in the operation and \nreinforce safe behaviors.\n\n34\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021OPERATING SAFELY\\\\ Safety\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nConnecting Pilots to Peers for Valuable Support\nAmerican has long offered an Employee \nAssistance Plan that provides emotional \nand mental support for our team \nmembers around the world. We know \nthat pilots, in particular, face unique \npressures every time they enter the \nflight deck.\n\nprofessional and personal lives, these \nvolunteers all undergo specialized, \nintensive training. As a result, they know \nwhen to lend a sympathetic ear and \nprovide encouragement or recommend \nother resources when the situation \nwarrants greater intervention. \n\nFor more than a decade, Project \nWingman has been providing our \npilots and their family members \nwith additional, specialized support \nwhenever they need it. Established by \nAmerican and the APA, this peer-to-\npeer 24/7 helpline allows pilots to \nreach out to other pilots for emotional \nand occupational support. Because it \nprotects the privacy of its users, Project \nWingman also alleviates any concerns \npilots may have regarding the stigma  \nof seeking help.\n\nMore than 40 pilots currently volunteer \nfor Project Wingman. In addition to \nbringing a unique understanding of \nthe challenges pilots can face in their \n\nProject Wingman is managed by a \ndeputy chair of the APA aeromedical \ncommittee, and American employs \na pilot at the managerial level on a \nfull-time basis to support and promote \nit. That includes visiting our pilot \ntraining programs to talk about it \nand meeting with the chief pilots on \na regular basis. Given the programs \nsuccess, he also advises other airlines \non their pilot mental health initiatives. \nThe U.K. and European Union require \nsuch peer-to-peer programs, and the \nFAA recommends them for all airlines. \n\nFor detailed safety performance data, see page 58.\n\n35\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021OPERATING SAFELY\\\\ Safety\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##SUPPORTING OUR TEAM MEMBERS\n\nCEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nThe airline business is labor intensive. At American Airlines, the 127,000 team members who support \nour customers and business are the single most important reason for our companys success. Across all these \nareas, American has made diversity, equity and inclusion (DEI) a priority. We have accomplished much \nand continue to invest in initiatives that build upon our progress.\n\nDiversity, Equity and Inclusion \n\nAmerican is implementing a multiyear strategy focused on \nembedding DEI throughout our organization. As the global \nleader in commercial aviation, we strive to lead the industry \nin DEI by:\n  Hiring, engaging and retaining the best and brightest \n\ntalent for growth\n\n  Delivering excellence in our operations to serve and \n\nexpand our global markets\n\n  Ensuring our teams reflect the diversity of our global \n\ncustomer base \n\n  Driving innovation to build competitive advantages\n\nWe have been intentional, innovative and timely in our \nefforts, making measurable progress quarter by quarter to \nbuilding a diverse workforce and an inclusive workplace. \n\nWe have invested in education, starting with the launch of \nmandatory implicit bias training in 2018. In 2021, approxi-\nmately 90,000 team members completed diversity training. \nAdditionally, in September 2021, we introduced a web-based \nInclusion Education Series. It Is designed to help each team \n\nmember become an upstander, with the first course focusing \non how team members can recognize when something is \nwrong, act to make it right and better understand microag-\ngressions.\n\nRetaining the best and brightest talent for growth\nIn 2021, American set representation goals to address our \nlargest gaps in leadership representation. We found that our \nbiggest opportunity for driving change required an initial \nfocus on our Black team members. Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nOur DEI commitment extends to our supply chain. \nIn 2021, we spent $291 million with approximately \n215 certified diverse suppliers (Tiers 1 and 2) and \n$318 million with 1,500+ small business suppliers.\n\nOur Community Council, which is composed of executives \nfrom different industries, also helps us deepen and expand \nour commitment to diverse and global markets. Council \nmembers have advised American on ways to improve \nthe travel experience for all our customers and provided \ncandid insight on our talent development, supplier \ndiversity and other efforts.\n\nDriving accountability and recruiting diverse talent \nIn 2022, we deepened our DEI commitment by introducing \na DEI metric into our short-term incentive plan, weighted at \n10%. We designed this new metric to drive accountability in \nthe specific aspects of our DEI program that we believe are \ncritical to our companys financial and operational success. \nThey include the following:\n  Increasing diverse representation among leaders\n  Retaining diverse leaders\n  Encouraging engagement by all leaders to increase \n\nawareness of the value diversity can bring to our business\n\n  Providing team members with training to help them \n\nrecognize and address bias effectively in their day-to-day \nwork at American \n\nWe are also expanding our recruitment efforts to attract the \nbest diverse talent to our organization. For example, we joined \nthe HBCU Partnership Challenge to promote greater engage-\nment and support between private companies and historically \nBlack colleges and universities. American also regularly \nparticipates in recruiting events organized by and for diverse \npopulations to ensure that we are their employer of choice.\n\n2021 Recruitment Partners:\n\nReceiving recognition for inclusion\nOur DEI efforts have received high scores from leading \nbenchmarks such as the Disability Equality Index, \nSeramount Inclusion Index and Human Rights Campaign \n(HRC) Corporate Equality Index (CEI). The latter rates \ncompanies on their policies and practices with regard to \nlesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and queer (LGBTQ) \nemployees. In receiving the CEIs highest-possible rating, \nAmerican was also designated as an HRC 2022 Best Place \nto Work for LGBTQ+ Equality.\n\nAmerican shares are also held by the NAACP Minority \nEmpowerment ETF, an exchange-traded fund that tracks \nthe Morningstar Minority Empowerment Index. According \nto Morningstar, this index is designed to provide exposure \nto U.S. companies that have embedded strong racial and \n\nethnic diversification policies into their corporate culture and \nthat ensure equal opportunities to employees irrespective of \ntheir race or nationality. To that end, American started using \nHiredScore in 2021. This hiring technology platform uses \nartificial intelligence-driven solutions to ensure accountability \nand mitigate potential hiring bias. \n\nDiversifying the flight deck\nAmerican was the first U.S. commercial carrier to hire both \na Black pilot (in 1964) and a female pilot (in 1973). However, \nour company and the aviation industry in general still need \nto do better in the pilots seat to mirror the DEI progress \nweve made elsewhere. We did make substantial progress \nduring the past year in hiring pilots that self-reported as \npeople of color, Black and women. With a large number of pilots retiring over \nthe next several years due to the FAA-mandated retire-\nment age, we find ourselves with a once-in-a-generation \nopportunity to change the face of the flight deck. Diversi-\nfying our pilot pipeline not only helps ensure that we have \nthe talent we need to support our customers, but it uplifts \ndiverse communities by providing individuals with access \nto well-paying careers with clear paths for advancement. \nAmong our initiatives, we expect our recently revitalized \nCadet Academy to play an important role. (See Developing \nthe Next Generation of Pilots on page 42.) \n\nBuilding on a long-standing commitment to pay equity\nAmerican has long championed pay equity, and we were \nproud to sign the White House Equal Pay Pledge in 2016. \nSince then, we have continued to refine our efforts to \nidentify and close pay gaps based on gender, race and \nethnicity. The 86% of our workforce that is covered by \ncollective bargaining agreements has built-in pay equity as \npart of those agreements. Therefore, we have focused on \npay equity for the remaining 14%, made up of management \nand support staff, who do not belong to unions.\n\nAfter engaging a labor and economics firm to support our \npay equity analysis, American began deploying Syndios \nworkplace equity platform in 2020. Through Syndios \nguidance, we fine-tuned our methodology and successfully \ncompleted pay equity reviews through 2021. Our approach \nbegins by placing team members in one of 50 similarly \nsituated groups (SSGs) across American based on the type \nof work they do. We then identify factors that can impact \ncompensation within each SSG, such as an individuals \nseniority, experience or pay scale. Of course, higher salaries \nawarded to any new or existing team members can result \nin unintended pay gaps. By running a pay analysis at key \npoints throughout the year, we can identify any drift in pay \nequity and address it. (See box at right.) \n\nIn 2021, American also became the first airline  and one of \nonly a handful of large U.S. companies  to receive Fair Pay \nWorkplaces inaugural pay equity certification. This Seattle-\nbased nonprofit is working to dismantle pay disparities based \non gender, race and ethnicity to create sustained fair pay. Our \ncertification means that American has committed to apply \n\nvalid methods for identifying pay equity issues \nand for implementing an ongoing remedia-\ntion plan over time. As such, our rules and \nstandards are available to the public.\n\nThe Fair Pay Workplace certification \napplies specifically to our management and \nsupport staff teams. Among our certification \nrequirements, American will undergo regular \ncheck-ins that involve a seven-point review of our remedi-\nation plan. We have also pledged not to ask job candidates \nabout their prior compensation or expectations for starting \npay, which Fair Pay has identified as one of the largest \nsources of pay gaps. \n\nIDENTIFYING PAY GAPS\nThe chart below shows Americans controlled pay gap for gender \nand race/ethnicity as of May 2022. We are among the more than 200 major companies that have signed the \nBusiness Statement on Anti-LGBTQ Legislation sponsored by the HRC and Freedom for \nAll Americans. \nOur commitment to supporting the LGBTQ+ community is also reflected in the benefits \nwe offer our team members. Thats why we signed the Fair Chance Business Pledge at the White House back \nin 2016, which helps eliminate employment barriers for those with a criminal record.\n\nIn March 2022, we furthered our commitment by joining the Second Chance Business \nCoalition (SCBC). Based on SCBC research, nearly 78 million Americans have a criminal \nrecord, and the unemployment rate among formerly incarcerated people is around 27%. \nThat is the highest rate in U.S. history, even when including the Great Depression. \n\nAs an SCBC member, we will share successful second chance hiring strategies with \nother companies and participate in the SCBC annual survey of hiring practices. We will \nalso play a part in other activities aimed at closing the employment gap for individuals \nin the criminal justice system.\n\nTalent Development\n\nAmerican gives our team members the tools and resources \nthey need to do their best work. To support this future growth, we know that we must develop a strong pipeline of pilot \ncandidates. Our Cadet Academy, relaunched in early 2022, will help us get there. \n\nAmerican designed this aviator training program to address the obstacles associated with traditional flight training. \nBy providing an affordable financing opportunity and a predictable path to completion, the Cadet Academy removes \nbarriers for anyone who wants to enter the profession. That includes women and people of color, who have long been \nunderrepresented. This is made possible by flexible loan options and predictable training costs. In addition, partici-\npants have access to the American Airlines pilot group as a resource for professional development and mentorship.\n\nAmerican has partnered with two highly regarded flight schools for the Cadet Academy: CAE in Phoenix, and Coast \nFlight Training, which has locations in San Diego as well as Dallas and San Marcos, Texas. Students are expected to \ntake approximately three years to complete the program as an airline-ready professional pilot. Among its eligibility \nrequirements, pilots must be at least 21 years old by completion. They are then guaranteed an interview with one \n\nof Americans three wholly owned regional carriers: \nEnvoy Air, PSA Airlines or Piedmont Airlines. Since \nwe have contractual flow-through agreements with \neach of these carriers, pilots who get hired have the \nopportunity to transfer directly to American once \nseniority accrues. \n\nThe Cadet Academy costs approximately $100,000, \ndepending on the school selected. Once accepted, \nstudents can apply for attractive variable- or fixed-\nrate loan options. These loans have no fees, do not \nrequire a co-signer and allow students to cover the \nentire cost of the Cadet Academy. Housing and meal \ncosts can be added, up to a $120,000 aggregate \nborrowing limit.\n\nComprehensive Benefits\n\nOur comprehensive benefits support the physical, emotional \nand financial well-being of our team members and their \nfamilies. One of the most popular new benefits in 2021 was \na medical option that provides team members with health \nreimbursement credits, to use now and in the future, when \nthey get an annual preventive exam. Each year theyre \nenrolled in the plan, team members can receive $500 for \nhealth care expenses to use today and $1,000 for health care \nexpenses in retirement. We also brought in SurgeryPlus, a \ncomplimentary concierge service that aligns team members \nneeding surgery with the most qualified and experienced \nsurgeons, coordinates scheduling from consults through \nfollow-up and consolidates almost all  if not all  services \ninto a single bill.\n\nThe following pages list some of the other core benefits our \nteam members enjoy:\n\nMedical, dental, vision and prescription coverage. Universal Declaration of Human Rights\n\nThe American Airlines Human Rights Statement applies to \nall team members and contractors, employees of our wholly \nowned subsidiaries, and our suppliers and other business \nrelationships. It is formally aligned with global standards, \nsuch as the U.N. Guiding Principles on Business and Human \nRights. We continuously evaluate our operations and value \nchain to identify, assess and address human rights risks \nand to engage key stakeholders.\n\nOur statement complements our annual team member \ntraining on the Standards of Business Conduct. We do not tolerate any retribution or  \nretaliation taken against any individual who has, in good \nfaith, sought advice or reported questionable behavior or  \na possible violation.\n\nAmerican has become an industry leader in combating \nhuman trafficking and child exploitation. We have \nmandatory human trafficking awareness training for our \nfrontline, customer-facing team members  including flight \nattendants, pilots and airport customer service represen-\ntatives  as well as for team members with international \npurchasing responsibilities. This training is required for new \nhires and as part of our recurrent training programs. We \nknow that vigilance is key in fighting the scourge of human \ntrafficking, and we stand ready to help.\n\nAmericans collaboration with government agencies, \nindustry partners and nongovernmental organizations is a \nkey part of our human trafficking prevention program. We \nwork with a range of partners, including the following: \n  The U.S. Department of Homeland Securitys Blue \n\nCampaign, a national public awareness effort that aims \nto educate the public, law enforcement and industry \npartners to recognize the indicators of human trafficking. \n\n  New Friends New Life (NFNL), a Dallas-based organi-\n\nzation working to restore and empower formerly \ntrafficked teenage girls and sexually exploited women \nand their children. By \nproviding access to education, job training, financial \n\nassistance and mental health support, NFNL helps \nwomen and their children overcome backgrounds of \nabuse, addiction, poverty and limited opportunities. NFNL \nhas held training sessions for more than 150 American \nteam members at our headquarters in Fort Worth, Texas, \nand another 50 at Miami International Airport. Despite the challenges \npresented by COVID-19 over the past two years, we continue to rigorously measure and track customer \nsatisfaction through passenger surveys  efforts that led to further improvements in our operations \nand the services we provide. \n\nAlthough comfort and convenience are essential aspects \nof our service offerings, we know that dependability and \nreliability are the foundation for meeting our customers \nneeds. Our chief priority is getting passengers to their \ndestinations safely, on schedule and with their baggage in \ntow, and we closely track our performance on these metrics. \n\nDriving record performance in customer satisfaction\nIn 2021, American safely transported over 165 million \npassengers, about 25% more than the next largest carrier. \nDespite the ongoing volatility in demand for air travel based \non the spread of COVID-19 and its emerging variants, we \nachieved our best performance in on-time arrivals, on-time \ndepartures and completion factor compared with any \npre-pandemic year in our history.\n\nOur operating performance was particularly strong during \nthe year-end holidays. In fact, our on-time performance in \nDecember 2021 outperformed any December in years prior \nto the pandemic, and American performed better than our \nprimary competitors in these key operational metrics during \nthe month. We achieved these results despite an increase \nin sick calls toward the end of the year due to the Omicron \nvariant, a challenge American managed with far less disrup-\ntion than other airlines.\n\nDriven largely by this performance, American posted \nrecord Likelihood to Recommend (LTR) scores for 2021. \nOur full-year score of 73.0 exceeded our target and \nreflected a 1.7% gain over 2020. Our score for the fourth \nquarter  75.6  was our highest ever recorded for a \nsingle quarter. LTR measures satisfaction on a scale of 0 to \n100 points based on a recent trip, and it strongly correlates \nwith on-time performance. Based on 2021 data, we see \nan average penalty of more than 20 points to LTR when a \nflights arrival is delayed.\n\nLTR also reflects other aspects of the customer journey at \nthe airport and in the air, such as check-in and boarding, \ncustomer service and onboard products. \n\nAlthough LTR is a commonly used metric across indus-\ntries, there is no industry standard methodology for \nmeasuring or reporting it. Our sampling of 2 million \ncustomer surveys reflects a representative mix of \ncustomers by segment relative to the passenger mix of \ncustomers who fly on a daily basis. This helps ensure a \nbalance of feedback from both AAdvantage members \nand nonmembers, making American more accountable to \nall our customers and helping us better understand their \ncollective priorities. \n\n47\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021SERVING OUR CUSTOMERS\\\\ Customers\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nOur mishandled baggage rate (MBR) rose to 7.63 in \n2021, due largely to the significant increase in flights and \ntravelers as we ramped back up operations. Our approach for identifying and \nmitigating cybersecurity risk is aligned with the National \nInstitute of Standards and Technology Special Program \n800-171. Our Chief Information Security Officer \nis responsible for cybersecurity and reports to the Chief \nInformation Officer, who is a member of our senior \nmanagement team. Our company \nalso has a cybersecurity training and awareness program \nfocused on educating our team members about cyber risk \nand our internal policies and procedures related to cyber-\nsecurity, privacy and compliance. \n\nAmericans privacy program, which is audited annually, is \nled by our Chief Privacy and Data Protection Officer and \nstaffed with certified privacy professionals. We also have a \nPrivacy Council, composed of more than 20 senior leaders \nwho meet quarterly to discuss privacy issues, challenges \nand proposed solutions. The council is supported by \napproximately 75 privacy liaisons across the business.\n\n49\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021SERVING OUR CUSTOMERS\\\\ Customers\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nThe privacy program is guided by key privacy principles \nthat inform how American handles and protects the \npersonal information in our care, such as responsi-\nbility, transparency, security and choice. Our Privacy \nOffice regularly conducts privacy impact assessments \nof business processes and supporting information \ntechnology (IT) systems that process personal data. \nThe primary role of these assessments is to identify and \nremediate associated privacy risks. \n\nInformation obtained from privacy impact assessments is \nused to populate our personal data inventory, which details \nwhat personal data our company stores, how it is used, \nwhere it is stored, with whom it is shared and for how long \nit is retained. We supplement these efforts by coordinating \nwith our IT department to implement privacy design \nrequirements into the architecture and operation of our \nsystems that store and process personal data. We also use \nthese processes to fulfill our legal requirements for handling \ndata rights requests and data disclosures via our internal \nand external privacy policies and statements.\n\nOur team members take privacy training courses annually, \nand the Privacy Office conducts individual training sessions \nwith different business units each year that address a \nvariety of privacy issues. We also coordinate closely with \nour Vendor Management and Corporate Legal functions, \nwhich provide input on privacy terms and provisions in our \nagreements with our business partners and vendors to \nensure that privacy issues are appropriately addressed.\n\nFor operational performance data, see page 54.\n\nProviding Travel Resources to Help Navigate the Persistent \nCOVID-19 Pandemic\nAs the pandemic extended into its second year  with travel \nrequirements shifting frequently depending on destination and \nother factors  American provided our customers with the \nresources they needed. We expanded the use of Sherpa, an \nindependent travel resource, to provide updates on international \ntravel requirements due to COVID-19 variants. We also continued \nto partner with VeriFLY to help customers understand and verify \ntheir travel requirements. Its mobile health wallet makes it easy \nfor passengers to upload negative COVID-19 test results, vacci-\nnation records and forms they need to get verified status for \ntravel. Our customers can also use the app to get mobile boarding \npasses and take advantage of dedicated and expedited check-in \nlanes at several airports.\n\nCustomers traveling internationally can now access our Ready to Fly checklist when viewing their eligible reservations \non aa.com and the American Airlines mobile app. The checklist outlines everything our customers need, including test \nand vaccination requirements, along with options to submit digital documentation and contact tracing information.\n\nReady to Fly also links to the VeriFLY app. Customers can now check-in online at aa.com, through the American \nAirlines mobile app or at the airport kiosk after receiving their green check mark from VeriFLY and head straight to \nthe gate. These new digital options save customers time at the airport and give them peace of mind that they are \nready to fly before arriving at the airport.\n\nAmerican also partnered with trusted COVID-19 testing providers to allow customers to take a test at a clinic, at \nhome before their trip or to order a test kit to pack for their return trip. Among our clinic partners, both GoHealth and \nCareNow each offer more than 150 locations in the United States. For at-home testing before a trip, customers can \norder a kit from LetsGetChecked. It offers a 48-hour turnaround time for results. Qured, eMed and Optum all provide \npackable test kit options for return trips.\n\n50\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021SERVING OUR CUSTOMERS\\\\ Customers\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##INDEXES & DATA\n\nCEO  Mainline and owned regional.\n**   Defined according to the International Civil Aviation Organization (Annex 13) and the National Transportation Safety Board (Part 830). Of the six mainline accidents in 2021, five involved turbulence that caused crewmember injuries. The sixth involved damage that occurred \n\nwhen the aircraft struck a light pole with a wingtip during taxiing; there were no injuries to customers or crewmembers as a result of this event. Of the two regional accidents, one involved a passenger injury that occurred during a turbulence event, when a passenger \nfailed to follow crewmember instructions to remain seated. The other was a crewmember injury during pushback from a gate.\n\n*** Defined to include enforcement actions by the FAA, the European Aviation Safety Agency or equivalent national authorities related to the regulation of aviation safety.\n   The majority of our risk assessments are performed proactively prior to implementing or revising systems/procedures. Americans comprehensive SMS covers safety risks and hazardous situations related to six areas: flight safety, flight service, ground operations, \n\ntechnical operations (maintenance), security and environmental. The figures reported here include all such risks identified by our SMS. The number of risk assessments increased in 2020 due to operational and staffing changes as a result of COVID-19; e.g., returning to \nservice aircraft that had been stored required risk assessments to determine readiness to fly.\n\n   Our SMS requires that we mitigate identified risks, particularly high risks, to as low as reasonably practicable (ALARP). These systemic and residual risks are monitored, measured and tracked.\n  Due to the slowdown in travel across the industry in 2020, American implemented an expansive temporary aircraft storage program throughout the network that resulted in a significant increase of aircraft on the ground, where damages are most likely to occur.\n\nTeam Member Safety Performance\n\n2021\n\n2020\n\n2019\n\n Learn more about whats happening at American by visiting \nnews.aa.com and connect with American on Twitter @AmericanAir \nand at Facebook.com/AmericanAirlines.\n\n1\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##MESSAGE FROM OUR CEO\n\nCEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nAs the world begins to emerge from the pandemic and \nreconnect, American Airlines is committed to living our \npurpose to care for people on lifes journey. People want \nto explore and make connections again, while businesses \nrecognize the importance of reestablishing relationships, \nand they are turning to American to make that possible. To \ndo so, we are focused on running a reliable operation and \nreturning American to profitability. And, thanks to the hard \nwork and dedication of our team, we are making strong \nprogress on both. \n\nOur environmental, social and governance (ESG) efforts \nare a key part of Americans success today and critical to \nbuilding a resilient airline that will thrive forever. At the \ncore, we are a people business, relying on our 127,000 \nteam members to fly millions of customers each year to \nthe important moments in their lives. Operating every \nflight safely and protecting the health and well-being of \nour team members and customers is the starting point for \neverything we do at American. \n\nWere also focused on ensuring we have the talent our \ncompany needs to grow and compete. Doing so requires \nrecruiting and advancing the best talent and creating a \nculture in which every one of our team members is valued, \nempowered and has the opportunity to grow at American. \nTo make that a reality, we are prioritizing diversity, equity \nand inclusion (DEI) throughout our organization. \n\nIm proud to say that in 2021 we met or exceeded the \ngoals we set to address our largest gaps in leadership \nrepresentation. We will continue to track representation \nclosely, because we know what gets measured gets done. \nIn 2022, we included DEI goals in the annual short-term \n\nincentive plan for our entire leadership team, encouraging all \nmanagers and above to be accountable for our performance. \n\nEqually essential to our long-term success is preparing our \nairline to thrive in a carbon-constrained future. To address \nclimate change, American continues to strive to achieve \nnet zero emissions by 2050 by running a more fuel-efficient \noperation, with more fuel-efficient aircraft, powered by \nlow-carbon fuel. In April 2022, we became the first airline \nin the world to receive validation from the Science Based \nTargets initiative that our intermediate emissions-reduction \ntarget complies with its rigorous criteria. In 2021, we used \nover 1.4 million gallons of sustainable aviation fuel (SAF), \nmaking us the only airline in the United States to report \nusing more than 1 million gallons of SAF. We also finalized \nagreements that bring our total SAF purchase commitment \nto date to over 120 million gallons. \n\nAs a result of these and other efforts, in 2021 American was \nincluded in the Dow Jones Sustainability North America \nIndex for the first time  the only passenger airline to be \nincluded. American is also proud to continue our support \nfor the United Nations Global Compacts Ten Principles, and \nour ESG efforts are integral to meeting that commitment. \n\nI am honored to add to the strong ESG foundation we have laid \nat American Airlines and to have the opportunity to support \nour incredible team as we build an even brighter future. \n\nRobert Isom | Chief Executive Officer\nJune 2022\n\n2\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##ESG STRATEGY\n\nCEO Message \\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nThe last two years have brought enormous change and disruption to our industry, economy and the \nworld. More than ever, rigorous management of environmental, social and governance (ESG) risks \nand opportunities is critical to the success of American Airlines and to the health of our planet. \nWe have long recognized the importance of these issues and have developed an integrated and \ntransparent approach to ESG management, measurement and reporting. That said, theres always \nroom for improvement, and we continue to look to best practices within and outside our industry  \nas we refine and strengthen our policies, practices and disclosures. \n\nOur Priority ESG Issues\n\nOur ESG strategy is focused on the topics that are most \nimportant to our company and our stakeholders. We \nperiodically conduct formal ESG materiality assessment \nprocesses, most recently in 2018, that serve as the founda-\ntion of our analysis of areas of risk and opportunity. And, \nthrough ongoing engagement across our company and with \na broad range of external stakeholders, we validate and, \nas needed, refine our assessment based on the input we \nreceive and changes in our operating environment. \n\nWe also continually monitor ESG trends, standards and \npractices relevant to our industry, and look to external \nreporting frameworks, including SASB and TCFD, as key \nindicators of investor perspectives on the most significant \nESG risks and opportunities for our company. In 2021, these \nactivities affirmed our focus on the following priority issues:\n  Climate change and fuel efficiency\n  Customer satisfaction and operational performance \n  Diversity, equity and inclusion (DEI)\n\n  Safety (including flight safety and team member health \n\nand safety)\n\n  Team member and labor relations\n\nDriving progress across all these issues is a key objective \nfor American. At the same time, we recognize that the \nbusiness landscape is evolving rapidly and that we must \nbe ready to address new areas of concern if and when they \nemerge. We will continue to seek stakeholder input while \nalso closely monitoring emerging ESG practices and trends. \n\nIn 2021, American joined the United Nations \nGlobal Compact, the worlds largest corporate \nsustainability effort. The index on page 53 guides \nstakeholders on where to find information on \nour efforts to implement the Global Compacts \nTen Principles.\n\n4\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\\\\ ESG StrategyESG STRATEGY\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nManagement and Governance \n\nSince ESG issues touch nearly every aspect of our \nbusiness, day-to-day management of individual elements \nis distributed throughout our operations and functions. \nAmericans Managing Director for ESG is responsible for \nguiding and coordinating our activities at the executive \nlevel. She receives guidance and feedback from a \ncross-functional and cross-operational group of senior \nleaders with responsibility for regularly assessing the \neffectiveness of our ESG strategy, its implementation \nand further integration of sustainability into our company \nstrategy and operations.\n\nAt the Board level, the Corporate Governance, Public \nResponsibility and Safety (CGPRS) Committee has primary \nresponsibility for overseeing ESG efforts. The CGPRS \nCommittee is regularly updated on the companys efforts \nrelated to sustainability and to addressing climate change. \n(See A Directors View on ESG on page 6.) \n\nClimate-related governance\nBecause climate change is a pressing challenge for our \ncompany and our planet, American takes a coordinated \napproach to ensuring we have robust governance of \nclimate-related risks and opportunities. It begins with \nBoard-level oversight and accountability and extends to \nour day-to-day operations. \n\nAmericans Board oversees our climate strategy as part of \nan enterprise-wide approach to risk management. Either as \na full Board or through one or more of its committees, the \n\nBoard reviews managements strategy and its assessment \nof material risks affecting our business. This includes \npotential climate-related risks. \n\nIn 2022, we formally assigned Chief Executive Officer \nRobert Isom, who also serves on our Board of Directors, \nwith responsibility for oversight of Americans climate \nchange strategy. In addition, climate-related issues are a \nstanding agenda item in the CGPRS Committees quarterly \nmeetings. The full Board receives updates as well at least \nthree times per year.\n\nAt the management level, responsibility for climate-related \nissues is embedded in senior roles across our company. \nFor example, the Airport Operations team does resiliency \nplanning for more frequent and severe weather events; our \nFuel Procurement team works to secure cost-competitive \nsupplies of sustainable aviation fuel (SAF); and our Flight \nOperations and Fleet Engineering teams are focused on \nimproving fuel efficiency in the air and on the ground. Our \nClimate Change Steering Committee  which is led by an \nExecutive Vice President and includes representatives from \nAirport Operations, Flight Operations, Technical Operations, \nCargo, Finance, Safety, People and Communications, Legal, \nGovernment Affairs and Investor Relations  provides \nguidance across these efforts. And Americans Managing \nDirector of ESG is responsible for developing and \ncoordinating the companys overall climate strategy and \ndriving its implementation.\n\nPublic Policy and Political Contributions\nPolitical, legislative and regulatory decisions can play \nan important role in Americans success, and we have \nadopted policies that guide our participation in these \nprocesses. Reflecting best practices, our Statement on \nPublic Policy Engagement and Political Participation \nprecludes American from using corporate funds for \ncontributions to candidates, political party committees \nand political action committees. Our Board reviews  \nthis statement annually and last approved a revision  \nin January 2022.\n\nWe do not use corporate funds for the election-\neering activities that the Supreme Court allowed in \nCitizens United. On the rare occasion when we do \nuse corporate funds to contribute to a state or local \nballot initiative or a 501(c)(4) organization, we have \ncommitted to disclose that contribution. In 2021, \nAmerican did not make any political contributions.\n\nThe CGPRS Committee oversees the companys \nmajor advocacy priorities and activities, political \ncontributions and principal trade association \nmemberships. For example, we have committed to \naligning our lobbying efforts with the priorities and \ngoals of the Paris Agreement, the international treaty \non climate change. In 2022, we will also assess our \ntrade groups alignment with this agreement and \ninclude that in our reporting. \n\n5\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\\\\ ESG StrategyESG STRATEGY\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  Climate Change \\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nHow do you view ESG in the context of the other priorities \nover which the Board has oversight? \nESG is an important part of Americans long-term strategy. \nWe dont look at ESG and other strategic priorities as \neither/or decisions. The health of people and planet are not \nseparate from the financial health of our company.\n\nCan you provide an example?\nLet me give you two examples. More than 90% of \nAmericans total carbon footprint comes from jet fuel, so \nour fleet renewal program and our work to run our flight \noperations more efficiently are an absolute win-win. Its \nthe same with DEI. The company that wins is the company \nthat has the best talent, and DEI is about having access to \nthe best talent available. If you create an environment that \ncombines empathy and action, where people with different \nperspectives and experiences can come together and move \nquickly and in concert, you get better decision-making \nacross the board. \n\nHow is your committee working to drive progress on  \nESG at American? \nYou have to examine performance, and you have to do that \nin a consistent way. The committee is deeply engaged on \nour climate strategy and receives regular updates about \nprogress toward our goals and data on our performance. Its \nthe same with safety, which is the backbone of American, \nas well as DEI. This year, we added DEI metrics to the \ncompanys management compensation plan, which is \nimportant because it clearly signals where the organization \nstands and propels progress. \n\nImportantly, the committee is trying to provide oversight \nin a way that is not boilerplate. We are looking for \nmanagement to talk to us about challenges and how theyre \nworking to find solutions. Even if we miss our goals, we can \ndig into why and what its going to take to correct course. \nA strong safety culture  which we have at American  \ndepends on zero blame, only learning. The same goes for \nother aspects of ESG. \n\nWhat does corporate leadership on ESG require?\nThere are categories of decision-making where the \ninformation and data arent perfect, but even with \nuncertainty, you can and must make decisions. That \ndoesnt mean you operate just on instinct or without \nthe facts, but you try innovative approaches with the \nbest information you have. Some will fail, some will be \nsuccessful  but progress depends on thoughtful action.\n\nBut one courageous company  or even several \ncompanies  is not enough to move the market or the \nworld. We need to build a cohort of leaders who are willing \nto work together and act boldly. Take climate, for example: \nWe need the environmental and scientific communities, \nbut we also need the business sector and government \nto step up. For our part at American, we recognize the \nurgency of climate change and that for our business  and \nfor our customers, shareholders and team members  it is \nin our interest to help find solutions, working with others \nboth within and outside our industry. Leadership requires \nthinking on a collective level, not solely an enterprise level.\n\n6\n\nIN CONVERSATION: \nA Directors View on ESG\n\nSue Kronick is the former Vice Chairman of Macys, Inc., \nand has served on the American Airlines Board of Directors \nsince 2015. In early 2022, she shared her perspectives on \nESG as an independent director and Chair of the CGPRS \nCommittee.\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021\\\\ ESG StrategyESG Change\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nAt American, we know that the challenge of climate change is acute and imminent, and we recognize \nour industrys contribution to it. We believe we have an obligation to our customers, team members, \nshareholders and the communities we serve to transition to operating a low-carbon airline. To make \nthat happen, we have set aggressive climate goals that match the seriousness of the challenge, and \nweve laid out a clear plan for how we will achieve them. \n\nOur aim is to achieve net zero greenhouse gas (GHG) \nemissions by 2050, and we have set an intermediate \ntarget to drive progress toward that goal. In April 2022, \nwe received validation from the Science Based Targets \ninitiative (SBTi) that our intermediate 2035 GHG reduction \ntarget complies with the SBTi criteria. That makes us the \nfirst airline globally to achieve this milestone. \n\nAmericans science-based target is to reduce carbon \nintensity, which means GHG emissions per unit of \npassenger and cargo payload that the airline transports, \nby 45% by 2035, compared to a 2019 baseline. In setting \nthis goal, we are committing to reduce the intensity \n\nIn 2022, American became the first airline \nglobally to receive validation from the \nScience Based Targets initiative (SBTi) that \nour 2035 GHG reduction target complies  \nwith the SBTi criteria. \n\nassociated with the entire life cycle emissions of jet fuel. \nThis includes both direct emissions (Scope 1)  which \nare primarily from the jet fuel used in flight  and the \nemissions from the production of the jet fuel the airline \nuses (Scope 3).\n\nAmerican has also committed to reduce by 40% the \nemissions from the production of the electricity we \npurchase (Scope 2) by 2035, also with a 2019 baseline. \nScope 2 emissions are a small part of our overall GHG \nemissions, but an important focus for reducing the \nimpacts of global warming.\n\nWe are also engaging with and supporting efforts to \ndrive broader action on climate across the public and \nprivate sectors. For example, American is a signatory to \nthe Business Ambition for 1.5C campaign, and we joined \nthe United Nations-backed Race to Zero. We are also an \nanchor partner, together with other leading companies, of \nBreakthrough Energy Catalyst (see page 13). We know \nthat our ability to achieve our climate goals depends on \nother actors  within the aviation industry and beyond \nit  and we intend to be a leader in helping drive the \noperational, policy and technological changes needed to \nadvance the transition to a low-carbon economy. \n\nOUR CLIMATE GOALS\n\nACHIEVED\n\nReceived SBTi validation  \nFOR OUR 2035 GHG EMISSIONS REDUCTION GOAL\n\nIN PROGRESS\n\nACHIEVE ABSOLUTE REDUCTION OF \n50m gallons of jet  \nefficiency initiatives \n\nfuel from fuel- \n\nBY 2025\n\nSOURCE \n\n2.5m GJs of  \n\ncost-competitive  \nrenewable energy\n\nBY 2025\n\nREPLACE \n\n10% of our jet  \nfuel with SAF \n\nBY 2030\n\nREDUCE \n\nGHG emissions  \nintensity by 45% \n\nBY 2035\n\nScope 2 emissions  \n\nREDUCE \n\nby 40% \nBY 2035\n\nAchieve net zero  \n\nemissions\n\nBY 2050\n\n9\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate Change\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CEO Message\n\n\\\\  ESG Strategy\n\n\\\\  Safety\n\n\\\\  Team Members\n\n\\\\  Customers\n\n\\\\  Indexes & Data \n\nquickly and be successful if lower-probability or higher-\nconsequence risks manifest. As a result, another core part \nof our strategy is making ongoing investments in deepening \nour understanding and analysis of climate-related risks \nand opportunities to inform our evolving approach. For a \ndetailed discussion of our climate-risk assessment process \nand findings, see page 22.\n\nAs part of our ongoing analysis of transition climate risks \nand opportunities, we incorporate a price on carbon when \nestimating Americans potential obligations under the \nCarbon Offsetting and Reduction Scheme for International \nAviation (CORSIA), European Union Emissions Trading \nSystem and other possible regulatory programs that may \nimpact our operations. The carbon prices used for these \nestimates are based on cost projections from respected \n\nOur strategy for reaching net zero emissions \nby 2050 is focused on running an ever more \nfuel-efficient operation, with more fuel-efficient \naircraft, powered by low-carbon fuel.\n\nexternal sources. We have also begun incorporating a \nshadow price on carbon in evaluating investments in our \nfleet and fuel efficiency initiatives, as well as sustainable \naviation fuel (SAF) purchases.\n\nOur Climate Strategy\nMore than 90% of Americans total carbon footprint, \nincluding our Scope 3 emissions, comes from our use of jet \nfuel, so our strategy for reaching net zero emissions by 2050 \nis focused on running an ever more fuel-efficient operation, \nwith more fuel-efficient aircraft, powered by low-carbon fuel. \n\nTo do so, we are working to drive progress across several \nkey levers  some of which we have the ability to influence \ndirectly, and some of which will require action and collabora-\ntion within our industry, across sectors and by policymakers. \n(See chart on the following page.) \n\nIntegrating climate risk into our strategy and investments\nUnderpinning our strategy is the in-depth analysis we \nconducted in 2020  and updated and expanded in 2022   \nto understand the climate-related risks and opportunities \nfacing our company. We studied their potential impacts on \nour business, operations and the broader environment in \nwhich we work under different warming scenarios. \n\nWhile there is considerable uncertainty about the \nlikelihood and operational and financial consequences of \nthese scenarios, the direction and potential magnitude of \nclimate-related risk is clear. Our strategy is designed to \nposition American to anticipate, mitigate and respond to \nclimate-related risks and to thrive in an uncertain future. \nIt includes making targeted investments to address the \ndemonstrated and high-probability risks associated with \nclimate change that may affect our business, such as the \nimpact of extreme heat on aircraft or of sea level rise at our \nmajor hubs. It also includes strategic investments, based on \nthe best available information, to enable American to adapt \n\n10\n\nAMERICAN AIRLINES ESG REPORT 2021ADDRESSING CLIMATE CHANGE\\\\ Climate
